called \u201cAlice in Wonderland\u201d - N.Sh.) (Sawyer 2000); \"Poor Liza\" (direct reference to [[Nikolay Karamzin|Karamzin]] - N.Sh.) (Chernov 1992).|language=Russian}}</ref> ([[Eye color#Changes in eye color|light eyes]] and symmetrical face with high cheekbones<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rbth.com/arts/2014/07/19/russian_beauty_secrets_revealed_37691.html|title=Russian beauty secrets revealed|publisher=[[Russia Beyond The Headlines]]|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref>) also have contributed to her general recognition and success in a country because [[MTV (Russian TV channel)|MTV]] was launched in Russia just in 1998.<ref group=\"note\">[[Lyubov Orlova]] performed the most famous \"[[Bayan (accordion)|bayan]] playing\" female dance on \"{{ill|Fighting Film Colletcion #4|ru|\u0411\u043e\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0438\u043a \u2116 4}}\" (1941), a series of motivational propaganda movies during [[World War II]] [https://youtube.com/watch?v=1i8UdkQwsC8&start=3367 ]. An official biography claims her distant [[House of Rurik]] ancestry [http://www.lubov-orlova.ru/bio/detstvo.html ].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mycityua.com/articles/people/2009/12/21/064447.html|title=\u0422\u0418\u041c\u0423\u0420 \u0411\u0415\u041a\u041c\u0410\u041c\u0411\u0415\u0422\u041e\u0412: \"\u0425\u041e\u0427\u0423 \u0421\u041d\u042f\u0422\u042c \u0424\u0418\u041b\u042c\u041c \u041f\u0420\u041e \u041b\u042e\u0411\u041e\u0412\u042c \u041e\u0420\u041b\u041e\u0412\u0423 \u0421 \u041c\u0410\u0414\u041e\u041d\u041d\u041e\u0419 \u0412 \u0413\u041b\u0410\u0412\u041d\u041e\u0419 \u0420\u041e\u041b\u0418\"|trans-title=[[Timur Bekmambetov]]: \"I would like to make a movie about [[Lyubov Orlova]] with Madonna. But it's just a dream\"|publisher=MyCityUA.com|date=December 21, 2009|archiveurl=https://www.liveinternet.ru/community/in_bed_with_madonna/post117094479/|archivedate=December 21, 2009| quote= Madonna could play Orlova very well. But for now, these are just fantasies|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://likeness.ru/blog/tag/%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%BD%D0%B0/|title=\u041c\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0430|trans-title=Madonna|publisher=Likeness.ru - fun similiarities|quote= TOP 4 Madonna likenesses: 1. Johnny Depp as [[Alice in Wonderland (2010 film)|Mad Hatter]] - 864 votes; 2. [[Sasha Gradiva|Sasha]] - 178 votes; 3. [[:ru:\u0420\u0443\u0431\u0446\u043e\u0432\u0430, \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430|Valentina Rubcova]] - 102 votes; 4. [[Nika Turbina]] - 88 votes|language=Russian|accessdate=September 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theblueprint.ru/madonna-bedtime-story|title=\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043f \u043d\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438: Bedtime Story \u041c\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b|publisher=The Blueprint|trans-title=Video of the week: Bedtime Story|date=August 16, 2017|accessdate=September 19, 2019|quote=Video has a lot of direct references to the Soviet director [[Sergei Paradjanov]]'s ''[[The Color of Pomegranates]]''|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://kinoart.ru/texts/otchayannye-poiski-madonny| title=75 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u0410\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0443 \u041f\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0435\u0440\u0443: \u041d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0426\u044b\u0440\u043a\u0443\u043d \u2014 \u043f\u0440\u043e \"\u042d\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0443\" \u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0447\u0430\u044f\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u041c\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b |trans-title=75 Years Alan Parker: Nina Tsyrkun about \"Evita\" and Madonna's Desperate Search (1997 article reprint)|publisher=[[Iskusstvo Kino]]|accessdate=February 19, 2019|date=February 14, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219100520/https://kinoart.ru/texts/otchayannye-poiski-madonny|archivedate=February 19, 2019|language=Russian|quote=Madonna is sincere and very convincing. And again she cries with a real tears}}</ref> For example, Madonna's infamous ''[[Swept Away (2002 film)|Swept Away]]'' movie remake was perceived a lot more positively by the Russian critics and public because of the resemblance to a cult [[1957 Cannes Film Festival|1957 Cannes]]-winning Soviet film ''[[The Forty-First (1956 film)|The Forty-First]]'' about a female [[Red Army]] sniper and her handsome [[White movement|Whites]] prisoner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/372684|title=\u0415\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0435\u0449\u0435 \u044f\u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b \u0432 \u044f\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0430\u0445. \u0423 \u041c\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b \u0442\u0435\u043f\u0435\u0440\u044c \u0434\u0435\u0432\u044f\u0442\u044c \"\u0417\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u044b\u0445 \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\"|trans-title=There are still butters in the buttocks. Madonna now has nine Golden Raspberries|publisher=[[Kommersant]]|date=March 24, 2003|accessdate=September 19, 2019|language=Russian|quote=The main conflict of the script resembles the film of Gregory Chukhrai \"The Forty-First\" (two class-alien people of different sexes find themselves on an uninhabited island), only it ends a lot less tragically}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kinopoisk.ru/film/18974/|title=Swept Away|publisher=[[Kinopoisk]]|quote=Russian Kinopoisk Rating compared: 5.817 (11 021), [[IMDb]]: 3.60 (14 759)|accessdate=September 19, 2019|language=Russian}}</ref> Madonna's children books, \"[[Yakov and the Seven Thieves]]\" especially, were also praised for adapting both Jewish [[agada]] plot/names and Slavic folklore names, the later ones most obviously borrowed from the operas: Sadko the Snake (''[[Sadko (opera)|Sadko]]'' by Rimsky-Korsakov), Olga (''[[The Maid of Pskov]]'' by Rimsky-Korsakov, ''[[Eugene Onegin (opera)|Eugeny Onegin]]'' by Tchaikovsky), Vladimir the Villain (''Eugene Onegin''), Boris the Barefoot Midget (''[[Boris Godunov (opera)|Boris Godunov]]'' by Mussorgsky), Igor the Tiger (''[[Prince Igor]]'' by Borodin).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecharmedbookshop.com/listing/552406439/yakov-and-the-seven-thieves-madonna|title=Yakov and The Seven Thieves - Madonna, Gennady Spirin|publisher=The Charmed Books|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dazzle.ru/music/mnseiatlpm.shtml|title=10 \u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044f 2005 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u043c\u043a\u0430\u0445 XVIII \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u043d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0438-\u044f\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0438 \u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u00ab\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0430\u00bb \u043f\u043e\u043e\u0449\u0440\u0438\u043b \u041c\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0443 \u0437\u0430 \u0435\u0451 \u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0439|trans-title=On September 10, 2005, during the 18th Moscow International Book Fair, the \"Russian Culture\" foundation praised Madonna for her literary work for children|publisher=Dazzle.ru|language=Russian|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref> Madonna's directorial and writing effort ''[[W.E.]]'', with [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] piano-playing immigrant character named Eugene (see the system of more than 3000 {{ill|Children music schools in Russia|ru|\u0414\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044b \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zen.yandex.ru/media/kultshpargalka/detskie-muzykalnye-konkursy-komu-oni-nujny-5d814ad5bd639600ad801afc|title=\u0414\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u044b: \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043e\u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0443\u0436\u043d\u044b?|trans-title=Children classical music competitions: Who needs them?|date=September 24, 2019|accessdate=December 5, 2019|quote=And since the cost of the stakes in music schools is microscopic (for reference: 9489 rubles ['''149 US dollars a month'''; stake means a teacher's montly salary for 18 hours a week]), this is a question of survival for the teachers|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.classicalmusicnews.ru/articles/bomb-for-music-schools/|title=\u0411\u043e\u043c\u0431\u0430 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b|trans-title=Bomb for the Children Music Schools|publisher=\u041f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b ClassicalMusicNews.ru|date=June 17, 2019|accessdate=December 10, 2019|language=Russian|quote=When [[Ray Bradbury]] wrote his dystopia ''[[Fahrenheit 451]]'', he did not suspect how close the future was... By hook or by crook, both through the door and through the window, high-ranking officials want to do something with children music schools... Or will we invite Chinese experts? So what? They have been preparing according to our system for many years now, since the industrial revolution began. There are many of them, just enough for us. And we are friends with China, we even export ice cream to them}}</ref> which was later adopted by [[China]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nsk.sibnovosti.ru/culture/376608-pianist-aleksey-skanavi-v-kitae-nasha-klassicheskaya-muzyka-schitaetsya-prestizhnym-zanyatiem|title=\u041f\u0438\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u0421\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438: \"\u0412 \u041a\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0448\u0430 \u043a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0447\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0436\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0437\u0430\u043d\u044f\u0442\u0438\u0435\u043c\"|trans-title=Pianist Alexei Scanavi: \"In China, our classical muusic is perceived as prestigious employment\"|publisher=Sibnovosti|date=August 13, 2019|accessdate=September 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/05/27/russia-builds-3-new-churches-a-day-orthodox-leader-says-a65755|title=Russia Builds 3 New Churches a Day, Orthodox Leader Says|publisher=The Moscow Times|date=May 27, 2019|accessdate=December 12, 2019|quote=It\u2019s not because we have too much money and don\u2019t know where to spend it on. Our people who have gone through years of atheism [under the Soviet Union] have realized with their minds and hearts that without God, nothing happens}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvzvezda.ru/news/vstrane_i_mire/content/20198231452-VK7sA.html|title=\u0412 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0443\u043c|trans-title=Russia sets a new living wage|date=August 23, 2019|publisher=[[Zvezda (TV channel)|Zvezda]]|accessdate=December 26, 2019|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ostrovrusa.ru/rosgvardiya-zarplata|title=\u041e\u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u043d\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0447\u0438\u044f: \u043a\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u0440\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0438\u0438|trans-title=Special powers: what salaries are received in the Russian Guard|date=September 21, 2019|accessdate=December 26, 2019|language=Russian|quote=[in 2016, state budget could allow the establishment of [[National Guard of Russia]] (340 000 men) with] a minimum salary for a private Guard (policeman) being 15400 roubles a month}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gorky.media/context/bethoven-byl-ne-nastolko-glup-chtoby-do-starosti-voshishhatsya-revolyutsiej/|trans-title=Beethoven was not that stupid to admire the revolution until his old age|title=\"\u0411\u0435\u0442\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0431\u044b\u043b \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0433\u043b\u0443\u043f, \u0447\u0442\u043e\u0431\u044b \u0434\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0445\u0438\u0449\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u0440\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044e\u0446\u0438\u0435\u0439\"|date=February 18, 2018|quote=If you return to the very image of the composer - for Soviet culture, Beethoven was an iconic figure|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapsinews.ru/judicial_analyst/20121128/265567726.html|title=\u041d\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043e\u044f\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0441\u0443\u0434\u0435|trans-title=Unbelievable adventures of American journalist in a Russian court|publisher={{ill|RAPSI|ru|\u0420\u0410\u041f\u0421\u0418}}|date=November 28, 2012|accessdate=September 25, 2018|language=Russian|quote= reminiscent of a typical school skirmish of \"bullies\" against \"nerds\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nybooks.com/daily/2018/03/16/ivan-ilyin-putins-philosopher-of-russian-fascism/|title=Ivan Ilyin, Putin\u2019s Philosopher of Russian Fascism|publisher=[[The New York Review of Books]]|accessdate=December 12, 2019|quote=The proper interpretation of the \u201cjudge not\u201d passage was that every day was judgment day, and that men would be judged for not killing God\u2019s enemies when they had the chance. In God\u2019s absence, Ilyin determined who those enemies were |date=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/693880|title=\u041e\u0442\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0446\u0438\u0440\u043a\u0430 \u043e\u0442 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 |trans-title=Separation of the circus from the state|quote=The thesis \u201ccinema is the most important of all the arts,\u201d was known to all the Soviet people. Only during the years of [[perestroika]] and glasnost' they were surprised to find out the quote meeting them in every movie theater did not fully reflect what Lenin said in 1923 to the head of education [[Anatoly Lunacharsky]]. The idea of 'the most humane person' leader favoring movies was perverted twice. In its original form, it sounded like this: \"While the people are illiterate, cinema and circus are the most important of all the arts.\" But it is likely that Lenin didn\u2019t say anything like that at all. In 1923 he was already seriously ill|publisher=[[Kommersant]]|language=Russian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://madonna.ru.com/en/memes/eva-polna-madonna-frozen|title=Eva Polna - Madonna (Frozen) (Odin v Odin!)|publisher=[[One to One!]] (Russia), official YouTube channel (transcript translated to English)|date=August 28, 2013|quote=I was worried, because in our country Madonna Ivanovna has a lot of fans|accessdate=December 28, 2019}}</ref><ref group=\"note\">State-sponsored system of {{ill|Children music schools in Russia|ru|\u0414\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044b \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438}} was aimed at preparing both the future consumers of classical music and the performers. It evolved from a first free music school for peasants established by \"[[The Five (composers)|The Five]]\" in the XIX century. In late Soviet Union, a cult of classical music was functioning as a replacement of religion using the main motto / credo, [[Dmitry Kabalevsky]]'s quote: \"Beauty Evokes Kindness\" ({{lang-rus|\u041f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0443\u0436\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0435|Prekrasnoe probuzhdaet dobroe}}) where [[Ludwig van Beethoven]], as [[Vladimir Lenin]]'s favourite composer, was an unfading idol to such a degree he even half-jokingly was referenced with [[patronymic]] \u2014 \"Ludwig I'''van'''ovich\".[http://uznaika.com/facts/3913-nash-lyudvig-ivanovich-betxoven.html ] A similar pattern was repeated with Madonna Ivanovna (her father's name has a local version of \"Selivan\" (main character from [[Nikolai Leskov]]'s \"{{ill|Bugaboo (Leskow)|lt=Bugaboo|de|Das Schreckgespenst (Nikolai Leskow)}}\"), which was generally shortened to \"Ivan\"). [[Russian Orthodox Church]] doesn't allow the use of music instruments in a church, as only choir and bells ringing are allowed, thus, the Communists-developed system of training piano, violin or balalaika players is almost useless, for a current political regime ideology based on [[Ivan Ilyin]] philosophy. [[Vsevolod Chaplin]], church official who urged ROC believers not to attend Madonna concert in 2006[https://ura.news/news/9066 ], shared in 2012: \"I don't like [[Mozart]]. I believe, to a large extent, this is [[Britney Spears]] of his time. With the exception of certain brilliant insights, he was writing monotonous and poppy things\".[https://www.fontanka.ru/2012/04/05/114/ ] For example, compare \"[[Vo Kuznitse]]\" (children folk song about [[burdock]]'s importance in intimate hygiene of XIX century Russians) performance by [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b7Bwgp0LnF0 children music school students choir], by [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YQi-gZddgho male church choir],  [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hpsf9ptyfKk TV-promoted version] by [[Sretensky Monastery]] Male Choir, and [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q0W1NMiYURI Alumni of the Yale Russian Chorus].</ref>) was retitled for theatrical release as ''WE. Believe in Love'' ({{lang-rus|\u041c\u042b. \u0412\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043c \u0432 \u043b\u044e\u0431\u043e\u0432\u044c|My verim v lyubov'}}), both to appeal a target audience and because of confusion with a well-known 1920s [[dystopia|dystophian]] novel ''[[We (novel)|We]]'' by  [[Yevgeny Zamyatin]]. Despite a harsh criticism by the most influential critic [[Anton Dolin]], the movie had an average [[Kinopoisk]] score 7.413 (13 508 votes)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kinopoisk.ru/film/484451/|title=WE. Believe in love|publisher=Kinopoisk|accessdate=December 10, 2019|language=Russian}}</ref>), with 50 percent of positive professional reviews, a significant difference from [[IMDb]] score 6.30 (11 487 votes)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1536048/|title=W./E.|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=2019-12-10}}</ref> and 37 percent of positive reviews<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radiovesti.ru/brand/61178/episode/1388598/|title=\u041c\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0440\u0435\u0436\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0451\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0443|trans-title=Madonna deserves a director's antineward|publisher=Vesti FM|date=September 2, 2011|accessdate=April 20, 2019|author=Anton Dolin|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104223439/http://radiovesti.ru/brand/61178/episode/1388598/|archivedate=April 1, 2018}}</ref> Seven years after the release, Madonna's movie made a list of instant classics: \"The film is about art's ability to recall a close connection between the past and the present\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.ru/msk/feature/484643|title=\u041e \u0447\u0435\u043c \u043c\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0438\u0442 \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e: \u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u044b, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0438\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043c\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u044c \u043a\u0430\u0436\u0434\u043e\u043c\u0443|trans-title=What is the art silent about: films that everyone should watch|publisher=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|date=April 15, 2019|accessdate=April 21, 2019|author=Nikitina E.}}</ref>\n\n== Madonna as an icon ==\nDubbed as the most iconic female artist of all time,<ref name=\"WMA\"/> Madonna is a synonym of vanguard in the fields of her work.<ref name=\"Moma\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/86958.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203021938/http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/86958.html|title=Impone tendencia la 'Chica material'|trans-title=Imposes trend, the Material Girl|language=Spanish|location=Mexico|work=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|archivedate=December 3, 2013 |date=November 2008|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref> By her impact and contributions, she [[Bibliography of Madonna|has been analyzed]] from the point view of [[Madonna Studies|several studies]], including feminist, sexual, gay, [[Queer studies|queer]], musical, [[Social studies|social]] and [[postmodern]] etc., becoming known as an icon in all these branches. Reader editor Brian McNair wrote that \"Madonna more than made up for in iconic status and cultural influence\".<ref name=\"McNair\">{{harvnb|McNair|2002|pp=69}}</ref> Professor Dennis Hall said that \"the fact that not only her work but her person was open to multiple interpretations contributed to the rise of [[Madonna Studies]]\".<ref name=\"Hall\"/> As Hall, [[Hao Huang]] in his 1999 book ''Music in the 20th Century'' wrote that Madonna has made a career as well as an art out of reinventing herself \u2014 as a rock diva, stage and screen star, video vixen, fashion icon, and cultural phenomenon.<ref name=\"Huang\">{{harvnb|Huang|1999|pp=386}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Madonnaicon.jpg|thumb|left|Icon of Madonna, taken in 1990 at the [[AIDS Project Los Angeles]]. Is created by [[Alan Light]].]]\nAcademics felt that [[Oxford English Dictionary]]'s recent definition of \"icon\" as a \"person or thing\" or an \"institution\", etc., considered worthy of admiration or respect or \"regarded as a representative symbol\", esp. of a culture or movement\u201d (OED 2009),can be used to describe Madonna.<ref name=\"Heindelber University\"/> Alyson Welsh from ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented that \"she is an amazing role model, and a [[cultural icon]]\".<ref name=\"GuardianWels\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2015/apr/09/why-madonna-is-still-my-style-icon-despite-the-look-at-me-lingerie|title=Why Madonna is still my style icon (despite the look-at-me lingerie)|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=April 9, 2015|accessdate=June 17, 2015|first=Alyson|last=Welsh}}</ref> The program [[Australasian Journal of American Studies]] (AJAS) remember that it's not an accident that [[Mickey Mouse]] and Madonna are worldwide icons.<ref name=\"AJAS\">{{cite journal|title=AJAS|date=July 1, 1996|accessdate=June 18, 2015|volume=15|work=[[Australasian Journal of American Studies]] (AJAS)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oelKAAAAYAAJ&q=It's+not+an+accident+that+Mickey+Mouse+and+Madonna+are+worldwide+icons&dq=It's+not+an+accident+that+Mickey+Mouse+and+Madonna+are+worldwide+icons&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=22CDVc20GcGz-AGc14K4CA&ved=0CBYQ6AEwAQ|page=60|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nProfessors from [[Heidelberg University]] shows how Madonna's \"iconicity\" is indeed that of a \"meta-icon\" in the sense that the self-reflexive imitation of celebrity poses. Calls this strategy \"iconizing\", in analogy to the concept of \"vogueing\". The essay also inquires into the blend of biography and performativity that can be said to underlie Madonna's \"iconizing\" in relation to the performance artists.<ref name=\"Heindelber University\">{{cite web|url=http://www.as.uni-heidelberg.de/personen/Leypoldt/files/LeypoldtEnglerAmericanCulturalIconsIntroduction.pdf|title=Cultural Icons, Charismatic Heroes, Representative Lives|publisher=[[Heidelberg University]]|accessdate=June 17, 2015|page=22}}</ref> [[Michelle Goldberg]] said that \"[[Andy Warhol]] did an enormous amount to change that idea in highbrow circles, but Madonna made it conventional wisdom to conflate art and commerce. She pioneered this kind of multimedia, 'life as performance art'.\"<ref name=\"salon2000\"/>\n\nBefore closing the 20th century, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine declared her as one of the most important cultural figures of this century.<ref name=\"cultural icon\">{{cite journal|last=Wexter|first=Erica|title=Reviews Madonna Ray of Light|date=April 1998|accessdate=April 7, 2013|volume=21|issue=3|work=ThirdWay|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h56sBy_z9eUC&pg=PA28|page=28|ref=harv}}</ref> [[Miranda Sawyer]], [[Jefferson Hack]]  and others authors called to her as a 21st-century icon.<ref name=\"Sawyer\">{{Cite book|isbn=0752890514|title=Madonna|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Hack\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/21252/1/madonna-21st-century-icon|title=Madonna: 21st Century Icon|first=Jefferson|authorlink=Jefferson Hack|last=Hack|work=[[Dazed]]|year=2008|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref> [[Andrew Morton (writer)|Andrew Morton]] wrote in his book ''[[Madonna (book)|Madonna]]'' (2002) that \"she is the undisputed female icon of the [[modern age]]\". Also cited as one of the most fascinating women and enigmatic in [[current history]].<ref name=\"Morton\">{{Cite book|isbn=1854794329|title=Madonna Paperback \u2013 March 27, 2002|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> ''[[Madonna in Art]]'' (2004) is a book by Mem Mehmet where included the work art by over a hundred artists, including [[Andrew Logan]], [[Sebastian Kr\u00fcger]], [[Al Hirschfeld]], and [[Peter Howson]]. The book is a testament to her unique global impact.<ref name=\"Mehmet\">{{Cite book|isbn=1904957005|title=Madonna in Art Hardcover \u2013 December 1, 2004|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> French biographer Anne Bleuzen wrote that she is \"interplanetary\",<ref name=\"Bleuzen\">{{Cite book|title=Madonna Belle reliure \u2013 18 novembre 2005|publisher=Amazon.com|isbn=2915957037}}</ref> and Italian author [[Francesco Falconi]] felt that she is an icon eternal.<ref name=\"ReginadelPop\">{{Cite book|isbn=8876155503|title=Mad for Madonna. La regina del pop (Italian) Perfect Paperback \u2013 January 1, 2011|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> Editor Eduardo Guti\u00e9rrez Seguro from Latin magazine ''[[CNN Expansi\u00f3n|Qui\u00e9n]]'' wrote:\n\n{{Quote|Her Majesty: music and pop culture would not be the same [without Madonna]. Madonna set a precedent never seen for a singer, before her, [[eroticism]] was not a ''must''\u2014per very disguised form it takes, in the scenes videos or lyrics\u2014. Feminism underwent a complete makeover and the formula surprise/offense the public has she placed in the Everest of show business.<ref name=\"Quien\">{{cite web|url=http://www.quien.com/espectaculos/2012/02/06/su-majestad-camaleonica-madonna|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203021938/http://www.quien.com/espectaculos/2012/02/06/su-majestad-camaleonica-madonna|title=Su majestad camale\u00f3nica: Madonna|trans-title=Her Majesty chameleonic: Madonna|language=Spanish|work=[[CNN Expansi\u00f3n|Qui\u00e9n]]|archivedate=December 3, 2013 |date=February 6, 2012|accessdate=June 23, 2015|first=Eduardo|last=Guti\u00e9rrez Seguro}}</ref>}}\n\n=== Music ===\n[[File:Madonna platinum record 2.png|thumb|upright|A platinum record for her album ''[[GHV2]]'' under [[Maverick Records]].]]\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' described her as a musical icon without peer,<ref name=\"Queenofpopalltime\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/readers-poll-the-queen-of-pop-20110706/1-madonna-0325148|title=At 50, has Madonna surpassed the Beatles?|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 6, 2011|accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref> while [[RTL Television]] Belgium said that \"Madonna is a key figure in the music\".<ref name=\"RTL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rtl.be/people/people/news/722985/apres-30-ans-de-carriere-madonna-cartonne-toujours|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517190045/http://www.rtl.be/people/people/news/722985/apres-30-ans-de-carriere-madonna-cartonne-toujours|title=A presque 30 ans de carri\u00e8re, Madonna cartonne toujours|publisher=[[RTL Television]] ([[RTL Group]])|location=Belgium|archivedate=May 17, 2013|accessdate=June 22, 2015|date=March 21, 2013|language=French}}</ref> Bill Wyman, editor of ''[[Chicago Reader]]'', wrote that she is a \"genuinely freakish figure in popular music\".<ref name=\"ChicagoReader\">{{cite web|url=http://acculturated.com/madonna-should-not-have-apologized/|title=Truth or Dare: Madonna's big lie|first=Bill|last=Wyman|work=[[Chicago Reader]]|publisher=[[Wrapports]]|date=June 20, 1991|accessdate=June 17, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626143644/http://acculturated.com/madonna-should-not-have-apologized/|archive-date=June 26, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> According to international media and critics, Madonna is the most influential female recording artist of all time,<ref name=\"WMA\"/><ref name=\"cnn2008\">{{cite news|first= Stephanie |last= Busari |title=Hey Madonna, Don't Give Up the Day Job!|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/SHOWBIZ/Movies/03/18/madonna.movies/?iref=mpstoryview|publisher=CNN|date=March 24, 2008|accessdate=April 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Blackmore\">{{harvnb|Blackmore|de Castro|2008|p=496}}</ref> and the greatest woman in music history.<ref name=\"Jojo\">{{harvnb|Regalado|2002|pp=11}}</ref><ref name=\"VH1Woman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1679384/madonna-music-greatest-woman/|title=Madonna Crowned \u2018Greatest\u2019 Woman In Music|date=February 12, 2012|accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher=MTV}}</ref>\n\nHer contributions on music are generally praised by critics, which have also been known to induce controversy. Tony Sclafani from company [[MSNBC]] felt that her Madonna's impact and effect on the future direction of music bests [[The Beatles]], even that quarter century after Madonna emerged, artists still use her ideas and seem modern and edgy doing so.<ref name=\"MSNBC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/26164523/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/has-madonna-surpassed-beatles/|title=At 50, has Madonna surpassed the Beatles?|first=Tony|last=Sclafani|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|date=December 8, 2008|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref> Laura Barcella in her book ''Madonna and Me: Women Writers on the Queen of Pop'' (2012) wrote that \"really, Madonna changed everything the musical landscape, the '80s look ''[[du jour]]'', and most significantly, what a mainstream female pop star could (and couldn't) say, do, or accomplish in the public eye.\"<ref name=\"Barcella\">{{harvnb|Barcella|2012|pp=}}</ref> Similar to Barcella, Joe Levy ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]'' editor in chief, \"opened the door for what women could achieve and were permitted to do\".<ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2008-08-14-madonna_N.htm|title=Pop icons at 50: Madonna|first=Edna|last=Gundersen|authorlink=Edna Gundersen|work=[[USA Today]]|date=August 17, 2008|accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[music industry]], Madonna was the first female to have complete control of her music and image.<ref name=\"100artist\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-artists-of-all-time-19691231/madonna-20110420|title=100 Greatest Artists: Madonna|accessdate=April 10, 2015|work=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref><ref name=\"MTVBio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/artists/madonna/|title=Madonna Biography at MTV|author=[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]]|accessdate=April 10, 2015|publisher=MTV}}</ref> Authors noted that before Madonna, [[record label|records labels]] determined every step of artists, but she introduced her style and conceptually directed every part of her career; the music industry was the foundation to permanently change the way the record companies treat artists.<ref name=\"Batanga\"/> Journalist Carol Benson wrote that Madonna entered the music business with definite ideas about her image, but it was her track record that enabled her to increase her level of creative control over her music.<ref name=\"Benson31\">{{harvnb|Benson|2000|pp=231}}</ref> Many years after, she founded [[Maverick Records]] became the most successful \"[[vanity label]]\" in the [[history of music]]. While under Madonna's control it generated well over $1 billion for [[Warner Bros. Records]], more money than any other recording artist's [[record label]].<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite journal|title=Hush Hush / The Monthly Dish On The Music Business|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FD4jKFVQOhMC&pg=PA58&lpg=PA58&dq=Maverick+Records+became+the+most+successful+vanity+label+in+the+history+of+music&source=bl&ots=DSbCJujpEh&sig=d1c_YvuqZdqCyextGE0xddh-r0Y&hl=es&sa=X&ei=hMgZVb6IEMXWUdiMgIAE&ved=0CEsQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=Maverick%20Records%20became%20the%20most%20successful%20vanity%20label%20in%20the%20history%20of%20music&f=false|first=Joe|last=Fleischer|date=October 1998|accessdate=March 30, 2015|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|issn=0886-3032|volume=14|issue=10|page=58}}</ref><ref name=\"KeyAchi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marqueecapital.com/key_achievements.php|title=Madonna Key Achievements|accessdate=March 30, 2015|publisher=Marquee Capital}}</ref>\n\nCritics felt in retrospect that Madonna's presence is defined for changing [[Popular music|contemporary music]] [[History of music|history]] for women's, mainly [[Rock music|rock]], [[Dance music|dance]] and [[Pop music|pop]] scene.<ref name=\"DeathandTaxes\"/><ref name=\"MSNBC\"/><ref name=\"Barcella\" /><ref name=\"Vh1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2014-11-12/madonna-like-a-virgin-30th-anniversary/2/|title=10 Things Millennials Don\u2019t Understand About Madonna|publisher=[[VH1]]|first=Chris|last=Rosa|date=November 12, 2014|accessdate=June 16, 2015|pages=1\u20134}}</ref><ref name=\"Kaplan\">{{harvnb|Kaplan|2012|p=32|quote=Madonna changed the way pop music thought of women}}</ref><ref name=\"FormanBrunell\">{{harvnb|Forman-Brunell|2001|p=531|quote=Madonna changed the face of popular music by bringing glimpses of feminism to maistream adiences}}</ref><ref name=\"RSS\">{{cite web|url=http://rollingstone.es/specials/view/mujeres-que-cambiaron-las-reglas-del-rock|title=Mujeres que cambiaron las reglas del rock|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|location=Spain|trans-title=Woman who change the rock rules|accessdate=March 27, 2015|date=April 14, 2012|language=Spanish|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110210540/http://rollingstone.es/specials/view/mujeres-que-cambiaron-las-reglas-del-rock|archivedate=November 10, 2013}}</ref> Also, she is cited that open the doors for the future [[hip-hop]] explosion and approach to sex to her music.<ref name=\"MSNBC\"/> Erin Vargo from online magazine in popular culture, felt that \"Madonna has fought for freedom of expression by female artists. Her legacy has paved the way for today\u2019s pop, hip-hop, and rock artists to get into their own groove\".<ref name=\"ACCULTURATED\">{{cite web|url=http://acculturated.com/madonna-should-not-have-apologized/|title=Madonna Should Not Have Apologized|first=Erin|last=Vargo|publisher=[[Acculturated]]|date=January 9, 2015|accessdate=June 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626143644/http://acculturated.com/madonna-should-not-have-apologized/|archive-date=June 26, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' stated: \"Madonna, whether you like her or not, started a revolution amongst women in music&nbsp;... Her attitudes and opinions on sex, nudity, style and sexuality forced the public to sit up and take notice\".<ref>{{harvnb|Fouz-Hern\u00e1ndez|Jarman-Ivens|2004|p=162}}</ref> ''[[The New York Post]]'' writer Brian Niemietz, who found that Madonna revolutionized dance music much the same way [[Elvis Presley]] invented [[gospel music|gospel]] and [[rock and roll]].<ref name=\"NYP\">{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2008/04/03/madonna-dont-preach/|title=Madonna Don't Preach|work=[[The New York Post]]|first=Brian|last=Niemietz|date=April 3, 2008|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Pop star ===\n{{Quote box|align=left|width=30%|quote=\"Madonna\u2019s influence reigns supreme on today\u2019s artists, her impact on pop culture through film and fashion may never be topped, and Madonna changed the role of women in pop music. She gave women power, the ability to do more than just record dance hits, and brought about change in the industry that gave birth to every single pop star today.\"|source=\u2014Author Art Tavana from company [[Spin Media]].<ref name=\"DeathandTaxes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deathandtaxesmag.com/221072/madonna-was-better-than-michael-jackson/|title=Madonna was better than Michael Jackson|first=Art|last=Tavana|work=Death & Taxes|date=May 15, 2014|accessdate=April 14, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nMadonna is a pop star icon.<ref name=\"Izod\">{{harvnb|Izod|2001|pp=79}}</ref> According to the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, Madonna is the first multimedia figure in the history of popular culture.<ref name=\"RockHall\"/> [[Peter Robinson (journalist)|Peter Robinson]] from ''[[The Guardian]]'' felt that \"Madonna pretty much invented contemporary pop fame so there is a little bit of her in the DNA of every modern pop thing\".<ref name=\"GuardianPopstars\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/mar/05/madonna-inspired-modern-pop-stars|title=Madonna inspired modern pop stars|date=March 5, 2011|accessdate=June 21, 2013|last=Robinson|first=Peter|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' of Spain wrote that \"Madonna became the first viral Master of Pop on history, years before the [[Internet]] was massively used.\" Madonna was everywhere; in the almighty music television channels, 'radio formulas', magazine covers and even in bookshops. A pop dialectic, never seen since The Beatles's reign, which allowed her to keep on the edge of tendency and commerciality\".<ref name=\"RSS\"/> Also, Caryn Ganz from the same magazine wrote that \"Madonna is the most media-savvy American pop star since [[Bob Dylan]] and, until she toned down her press-baiting behavior in the nineties, she was the most consistently controversial one since [[Elvis Presley]].<ref name=\"RSBiography\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/madonna/biography|title=Madonna Biography|work=Rolling Stone|first=Caryn|last=Ganz|accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref> Music critic [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] felt that \"one of Madonna's greatest achievements is how she has manipulated the media and the public with her music, her videos, her publicity, and her sexuality\".<ref name=\"MTVBio\"/> Becky Johnston from ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine commented: \"[F]ew public figures are such wizards at manipulating the press and cultivating publicity as Madonna is. She has always been a great tease with journalists, brash and outspoken when the occasion demanded it, recalcitrant and taciturn when it came time to pull back and slow down the striptease\".<ref>{{harvnb|Metz|Benson|1999|p=55}}</ref>\n\nAcademic Becca Cragin explain that \"Madonna has managed to hold the public's attention for 30 years now, in large part because of her skillful use of the visual in expressing herself and marketing her music\".<ref name=\"Cleveland\"/> French academic Georges-Claudes Guillbert wrote that taking some elements and transforms them into commercial products. Cultural critic, [[Douglas Kellner]] explained that Madonna's popularity also requires focus on audiences, not just as individuals, but as members of specific groups.<ref name=\"UCLA\">{{cite web|url=https://pages.gseis.ucla.edu/faculty/kellner/papers/SAGEcs.htm|title=Culture Studies, Multiculturalism, and Media Culture by Douglas Kellner|publisher=[[University of California, Los Angeles]]|first=Douglas|last=Kellner|authorlink=Douglas Kellner|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Journalist [[Mark Watts (journalist)|Mark Watts]] felt that the rise and (perceived) decline of Madonna has gone, so to say, hand-in-hand with that of [[postmodern theory]].<ref name=\"Cambridge\">{{cite web|url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=3023292|title=Electrifying Fragments: Madonna and Postmodern Performance|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|first=Mark|last=Watts|authorlink=Mark Watts (journalist)|accessdate=June 20, 2015|issue=46|volume=12|date=May 1996|pages=99\u2013107}}</ref> According to journalist [[Annalee Newitz]], \"the academics in the fields of [[theology]] to [[queer studies]] have written literally volumes about what Madonna's fame means for [[gender relations]], [[American culture]], and the [[future]]\".<ref name=\"Newitz\"/> As Newitz, author in ''Images of women in American popular culture'' (1995) said that Madonna had reached such staggering celebrity that scholarly and popular assessments of the meaning of her work for the future of feminism, for the sexual values of the young.<ref>{{harvnb|Dorenkamp|1995|p=149}}</ref> In this way, many authors, including [[Alvin Hall]] and [[Matthew Rettenmund]] (''[[Encyclopedia Madonnica]]''; 1995), agree that Madonna is \"the world's greatest artist\" while others classify her as \"the most powerful celebrity or famous woman in the world\".<ref name=\"AdamSexton\"/><ref name=\"RettenmundBook\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rplwQgAACAAJ|title=Encyclopedia Madonnica|accessdate=February 22, 2015|quote= [[Norman Mailer]] thinks she's our \"greatest living female artist.\" In short, Madonna is the biggest star in the world.|isbn=9780312117825|author1=Rettenmund|first1=Matthew|date=March 15, 1995}}</ref><ref name=\"AlvinHall\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/worlds_most_powerful/3236338.stm|title=Your comments|publisher=BBC News|date=November 25, 2003|accessdate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> Music editor Bill Friskics-Warren wrote that \"Madonna's megastardom and cultural ubiquity had made her as much a social construct as anything else, a \"person-turned-idea,\" as Steve Anderson put it, along the iconic lines of Elvis Presley or Marilyn Monroe\".<ref>{{harvnb|Friskics-Warren|2006|p=63}}</ref>\n\n=== Mainstream ===\n{{See also|Records and achievements of Madonna}}\n\n[[File:Madonna Frozen painting.jpg|thumb|A painting inspired by Madonna's look on the music video of \"[[Frozen (Madonna song)|Frozen]]\". The released of ''[[Ray of Light]]'' increased the popularity of traditional [[Culture of Asia|Asian culture]] in American popular culture.]]\n\nCalled to as a \"mainstream hero\" by professor [[Karlene Faith]],<ref name=\"Faith\">{{cite book|jstor=10.3138/j.ctt2tv4xw#|title=Madonna, Bawdy & Soul|last=Faith|first=Karlene|author-link=Karlene Faith|date=1997|publisher=University of Toronto Press}}</ref> Madonna is [[List of best-selling music artists|the best-selling woman artist in the history]],<ref name=\"WMA\"/> and the most successful female recording artist of all time certified by ''[[Guinness Book of Worlds Records]]''.<ref name=\"mostsuccessful\">{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=55387|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040904205619/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/content_pages/record.asp?recordid=55387|title=Most Successful Female Solo Artist|editor-last=Glenday|editor-first=Craig|editor-link=Craig Glenday|work=[[Guinness Book of World Records]]|archivedate=September 4, 2004 |accessdate=April 13, 2015}}</ref> With several critics feeling that she paved the way for every female artist,<ref name=\"Vh1\"/> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine expressed that \"every pop star of the last two or three decades has Madonna to thank in some part for his or her success\".<ref name=\"Time\">{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2029774_2029776_2031853,00.html|title=The 25 Most Powerful Women of the Past Century|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|first=Michelle|last=Castillo|date=November 18, 2010|accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref> She is cited like an influence by [[List of artists influenced by Madonna|many other artists worldwide]].\n\nHer [[Super star|superstardom]] also is cited as the motivation of the success commercial and popularised or introduction of several things like branches, terms, groups, cultures, persons and products. For example, the media cited her acting in the movie ''[[Evita (1996 film)|Evita]]'', that popularised Argentinian politics and she put the nation [[Malawi]] on the map while she launched the trend for celebrity adoption.<ref name=\"WMA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldmusicawards.com/index.php/news/how-madonna-changed-world/|title=How Madonna changed the World!|publisher=[[World Music Awards]]|date=August 13, 2013|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Mirror\"/> Madonna's success open to other celebrities such as singers, actors and politicians have successfully dabbling in the publishing field for [[Children literature|young audiences]].<ref name=\"TheGuardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/nov/03/booksforchildrenandteenagers.familyandrelationships|title=Once upon a time|date=November 3, 2006|accessdate=June 18, 2015|work=The Guardian|first=Ed|last=Pilkington}}</ref> [[Mark Blankenship]] felt her first book ''[[Sex (book)|Sex]]'' \"changed publishing history\".<ref name=\"MarkBlankenship\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/madonna-sex-boo/10/2012/|title=My Weird Journey With Madonna\u2019s \u2018Sex\u2019 Book|date=October 22, 2012|accessdate=April 8, 2015|publisher=[[Logo TV|NewNowNext.com]]|authorlink=Mark Blankenship|first=Mark|last=Blankenship|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130831025639/http://www.newnownext.com/madonna-sex-boo/10/2012/|archive-date=August 31, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Her album ''[[Something to Remember]]'' set a trend of releasing ballad albums afterward, such as the 1996 albums ''[[Love Songs (Elton John album)|Love Songs]]'' by [[Elton John]] and ''[[If We Fall in Love Tonight]]'' by [[Rod Stewart]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=New Sets Offer 'Greatest Ballads'|first=David|last=Sprague|work=Billboard|issn=0006-2510|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ugkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA15#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=15|accessdate=April 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe popularizing the [[Vogue (dance)|Voguing]]. Academic Stepehn Ursprung from [[Smith College]] felt that \"Madonna created a market for Voguing in the commercial entertainment world\". Analyzed that \"through a close connection with the continued commercial success of Madonna, Voguing has left its mark on the world largely... Voguing was first appropriated by pop culture by pop music icon Madonna\".<ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite web|url=http://sophia.smith.edu/blog/danceglobalization/2012/05/01/voguing-madonna-and-cyclical-reappropriation/|title=Voguing: Madonna and Cyclical Reappropriation|publisher=[[Smith College]]|date=May 1, 2012|accessdate=June 18, 2015|first=Stephen|last=Ursprung}}</ref> The website Wallblog ([[Haymarket Media Group]]) from United Kingdom called tentatively in a question, to [[Yahoo!]] like the \"Madonna of digital media\".<ref name=\"Wall\">{{cite web|url=http://wallblog.co.uk/2013/05/31/is-yahoo-the-madonna-of-digital-media/|title=Is Yahoo the Madonna of digital media?|publisher=Wallblog ([[Haymarket Media Group]])|location=United Kingdom|date=May 31, 2013|last=Kane|first=Same|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Even, is cited that she has carried the [[burlesque]] to [[mass culture]].<ref name=\"Totem\"/> As is cited that MTV helped her, some authors like Josue Rich from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' felt that Madonna helped make [[MTV]] (alongside [[Michael Jackson]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,285759,00.html|title=Madonna Banned|author=Joshua Rich|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 20, 1998|accessdate=March 14, 2013|quote=Madonna helped make MTV ''as much as [MTV] helped make her,'' says Mark Bego, author of Madonna: Blonde Ambition..}}</ref> Biographer Mick St Michael wrote that \"[[girl power]] began with Madonna\".<ref name=\"90Mick\">{{Cite book|isbn=0711977348|title=Madonna: In Her Own Words (In Their Own Words) Paperback \u2013 December 31, 1990|publisher=Amazon.com|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/madonnainherownw0000stmi}}</ref> Also, she has credit for the introduction of [[electronic music]] to the stage of [[popular music]],<ref name=\"ROL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/ray-of-light-mt0004973231|title=Ray of Light - Madonna|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|first=Liana|last=Jonas|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> and innovated the [[rave]] culture.<ref name=\"OBrien\">{{harvnb|O'Brien|2002|pp=485\u2013489}}</ref><ref name=\"Harrison\">{{harvnb|Harrison|2011|p=4}}</ref> Similar, music critic [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] felt that Madonna introduced the dance pop to mainstream scene.<ref name=\"MadonnaReview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/madonna-mw0000268192|title=Madonna - Madonna review|publisher=Allmusic. Rovi Corporation|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|accessdate=June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to some cultural critics like [[Douglas Kellner]], the phenomenon of femininity inspired by [[South Asia]] as a tendency in Western media could go back to February 1998 when the pop icon Madonna released her video for \"[[Frozen (Madonna song)|Frozen]]\". They explained that \"although Madonna did not initiate the Indian fashion accessories beauty [...] took the public eye to attract the attention of the global media.<ref name=\"Hammer\">{{harvnb|Hammer|Kellner|2009|pp=502\u2013503}}</ref> The Spanish style of Madonna in the video \"[[La Isla Bonita]]\" became popular and was reflected in fashion trends of the time in the form of \"boleros\", skirts with tables and rosaries and crucifixes as accessories.<ref name=\"Clerk\">{{harvnb|Clerk|2002|p=44}}</ref> According to the official website of the city [[Safed]], Madonna popularized the [[Jewish mysticism]].<ref name=\"Safed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.safed.co.il/city-of-kabbalah-html|title=Tzfat, The City of Kabbalah|publisher=[[Safed]]|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Madonna set a trend that influenced people to take interest in the sexuality of women's bodies.<ref name=\"ImpactYahoo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukessays.co.uk/essays/history/the-cultural-significance-of-madonna.php|title=The cultural significance of Madonna|work=UK Essays|date=August 5, 2005|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=October 2015}} In general, some authors like entertainment critic Rogelio Segoviano felt that \"the fever for queen of pop does not yield to the passage of time\".<ref name=\"ElUniversal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.domingoeluniversal.mx/historias/detalle/Todos+quieren+con+Madonna-1070 |title=TODOS QUIEREN CON MADONNA |trans-title=Everybody wants with Madonna |first=Segoviano |last=Rogelio |work=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]] |location=Mexico |date=November 18, 2012 |accessdate=April 15, 2015 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223224203/http://www.domingoeluniversal.mx/historias/detalle/Todos%2Bquieren%2Bcon%2BMadonna-1070 |archivedate=February 23, 2015 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\n=== Fashion ===\n[[File:Madonna's Blond Ambition Corset.jpg|left|thumb|upright|Iconic corset made by fashion designer [[Jean Paul Gaultier]] that Madonna wore during her 1990 [[Blond Ambition World Tour]].]]\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' included her as one of the Top 100 Icons of all time in fashion, style and design.<ref name=\"TimeFashionICon\"/> Critics praised Madonna's style during her career, which became the defining look in the 80s.<ref name=\"Mirror\">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/madonnas-55th-birthday-55-ways-2175047|title=Happy 55th Birthday Madonna! Here are 55 ways you changed the world|first=Kate|last=Wills|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=August 16, 2013|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref> This gave rise to the term of [[Madonna wannabe]]. To experts in the 1990s, her use of fashion was even more eclectic.<ref name=\"Oh\">{{harvnb|Benstock|Ferriss|1994|p=172}}</ref>\n\nJournalist Michael Pye felt that \"the face that launched a thousand fashions. To a large extent Madonna not only makes fashion, she is fashion.<ref name=\"Claude37\">{{harvnb|Claude|2002|pp=37}}</ref> Editor of ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine [[Anna Wintour]] declared:\n{{Quote|She's a perfect example of how popular culture and street style now influence the world of fashion. Over the years, Madonna has been one of the most potent style setters of our time. She, just as much as [[Karl Lagerfeld]], makes fashion happen.<ref name=\"Claude37\"/>|sign=|source=}}\n\nProfessors in ''Oh Fashion'' (1994) book wrote that \"the Madonna phenomenon suggests that in a postmodern image culture identity is constructed through image and fashion, involving one's look, pose, and attitude. Fashion and identity for Madonna are inseparable from her aesthetic practices, from her cultivation of her image in her music videos, films, TV appearances, concerts, and other cultural interventions\".<ref name=\"Oh2\">{{harvnb|Benstock|Ferriss|1994|p=176}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' declared that \"no pop diva has reinvented her fashion image with the consistency and creativity of Madonna... she evolved into a fashion-forward icon whose sense of style became as influential as her chart-topping tunes\".<ref name=\"BillboardFashion\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/photos/428558/madonnas-fashion-evolution-her-most-iconic-looks|title=Madonna's Fashion Evolution: Her Most Iconic Looks|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=March 22, 2012|accessdate=June 15, 2015}}</ref> Similarly, editor of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' Dana Oliver comments why Madonna is the ultimate style chameleon and added that \"no one has transformed herself like Madonna. She has had about as many looks as she has records. Her ability to constantly reinvent herself and her music has helped to secure her status as an icon, and she has influenced a generation of copycats. In short, no one has had more diverse looks than Madonna\".<ref name=\"THP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/08/15/madonna-style-transformation-photos_n_3763575.html|title=Why Madonna Is The Ultimate Style Chameleon|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=August 16, 2013|accessdate=June 19, 2015|last=Oliver|first=Dana}}</ref>\n\nChloe Wyma from [[Louise Blouin Media]] commented that Madonna's chameleon attitude in transforming her fashion has become a universally recognized fact.<ref name=\"Blouin\">{{cite web|url=http://mx.blouinartinfo.com/news/story/950144/madonna-a-los-55-anos-de-edad-existe-otro-momento-mejor-para|title=Madonna a los 55 a\u00f1os de edad: \u00bfexiste otro momento mejor para examinar sus contribuciones a la moda y el feminismo?|trans-title=Madonna to 55 years: Is there another better moment to examine her contributions to fashion and feminism?|accessdate=June 10, 2015|publisher=[[Louise Blouin Media]]|first=Wyma|last=Chloe|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130904062204/http://mx.blouinartinfo.com/news/story/950144/madonna-a-los-55-anos-de-edad-existe-otro-momento-mejor-para|archive-date=September 4, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Ana Laglere from [[Batanga Media]] expressed that \"each new Madonna's style is a trend and is used by major designers as inspiration, flooding our world with innovative ideas\".<ref name=\"Batanga\">{{cite web|url=http://musica.batanga.com/9637/9-razones-que-explican-por-que-madonna-es-la-reina-del-pop-de-todos-los-tiempos|title=9 razones que explican por qu\u00e9 Madonna es la Reina del Pop de todos los tiempos|trans-title=9 reasons explain why Madonna is the Queen of Pop of all time|first=Laglere|last=Ana|publisher=[[Batanga Media|Batanga.com]]|date=April 14, 2015|accessdate=June 10, 2015|language=Spanish|pages=1\u20138}}</ref>\nCynthia Robins from ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' said that \"when Madonna came along, all fashion hell broke loose. Thus far, her influence on fashion  \u2014high, low and otherwise\u2014 has transmogrified from 'Who's That Girl?' to what in the world will Madonna wear next?\".<ref name=\"SF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/The-Material-Girl-Madonna-s-fashion-sense-has-2882599.php|title=The Material Girl Madonna's fashion sense has|first=Cynthia|last=Robins|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=September 2, 2001|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Alessandra Codinha from ''Vogue'' named as \"the master of reinvention\".<ref name=\"VogueM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/13253338/madonna-ghosttown-music-video-look/|title=Exclusive! Madonna on the Look of Her New Ghosttown video|first=Alessandra|last=Codinha|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=April 7, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Feminism ===\nMadonna as a feminist icon has generated variety of opinions worldwide. She is frequently associated with the [[feminist movement]] and she is considered a revolutionary figure who questioned the boundaries of gender. She is also responsible for influencing the mentality and behavior of women and how society interprets these changes.<ref name=\"Batanga\"/> Professor [[Sut Jhally]] felt that \"Madonna is as an almost sacred feminist icon\".<ref name=\"Sut Jhally\">{{harvnb|Jhally|2006|p=194}}</ref> Academic [[Camille Paglia]] from [[University of the Arts (Philadelphia)|University of the Arts]] called Madonna a \"true feminist\" and noted that \"she exposes the puritanism and suffocating ideology of [[American feminism]], which is stuck in an adolescent whining mode\". According to her, \"Madonna has taught young women to be fully female and sexual while still exercising total control over their lives\".<ref name=\"Paglia\">{{cite news|last=Paglia|first=Camille|authorlink=Camille Paglia|title=Madonna \u2013 Finally, A Real Feminist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/12/14/opinion/madonna-finally-a-real-feminist.html|accessdate=June 17, 2015|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 14, 1990}}</ref> Psychologist Jule Eisenbud in ''Sex Symbols'' (1999) noted that Madonna's refusal to accept that power and femininity is equivalent to masculinity has allowed her to maintain her status as a sex symbol.<ref name=\"Eisenbud\">{{harvnb|Eisenbud|Leigh-Kile|1999|p=15}}</ref>\n\n[[Jessica Valenti]] wrote in her book ''[[Madonna and Me: Women Writers on the Queen of Pop]]'' (2012) \"sure, one [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Madonna]] gave birth to Jesus... but our Madonna gave birth to \"femme-inism\".<ref name=\"Barcella2\">{{Cite book|isbn=1593764294|title=Madonna and Me: Women Writers on the Queen of Pop Paperback \u2013 March 6, 2012|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref> Spanish newspaper ''[[Peri\u00f3dico Diagonal]]'' convened a researchers panel discussion her as a feminist icon.<ref name=\"Totem\">{{cite web|url=https://www.diagonalperiodico.net/culturas/madonna-icono-feminista-o-totem-consumista.html|title=Madonna: \u00bficono feminista o t\u00f3tem consumista?|author=Victor Lenore & Irene G. Rubio|work=[[Peri\u00f3dico Diagonal]]|trans-title=Madonna: feminist icon or consumerist totem?|date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=June 18, 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> One of the comments, included that \"she democratized the idea of women as protagonists and as agents of their own action\", while some ambiguous ones stated that she contributed to women's empowerment of a few Western women, straight and gay middle class, but that empowerment is not feminism, because it is individualistic. Madonna was included in ''[[The Guardian]]'' list of the Top 100 women and editor Homa Khaleeli declared \"no matter the decade or the fashion, she has always been frank about her toughness and ambition\". She is still one of the most famous women on the planet and \"she inspires not because she gives other women a helping hand, but because she breaks the boundaries of what's considered acceptable for women\".<ref name=\"QReinvention\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/mar/08/madonna-100-women|title=Madonna |date=March 8, 2011|accessdate=June 18, 2015|work=The Guardian|first=Homa|last=Khaleeli}}</ref> She was also included in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's list of the 25 most powerful women in the 20th century.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\n=== Sex symbol ===\nMadonna has been referred to as a sexual icon,<ref name=\"Shaded\"/><ref name=\"Sex icon\">{{cite news|title=Madonna|url=http://newint.org/features/1991/08/05/reviews/|accessdate=June 17, 2015|newspaper=[[New Internationalist]]|date=August 5, 1991}}</ref> and [[sex symbol]]; most notable in the decade of the 1980s and 1990s.<ref name=\"Various\">{{harvnb|Gregg|McDonogh|Wong||p=}}</ref> Also, she is cited as an icon of sexual freedom and expression.<ref name=\"ReginadelPop\"/> Author Courtney E. Smith in the 2011 book ''Record Collecting for Girls'' noted that most people associate Madonna with sex.<ref name=\"SmithGaga\">{{harvnb|Smith|2011|pp=119}}</ref> [[Chuck Klosterman]] in his book ''[[Sex, Drugs, and Cocoa Puffs]]'' (2003) wrote that \"whenever I hear intellectuals talk about sexual icons of the present day, the name mentioned most is Madonna\".<ref name=\"Chris\">{{harvnb|Klosterman|2003|p=}}</ref> Even, Karen Fredericks from socialist newspaper ''[[Green Left Weekly]]'' in comment with her sexual attitude said that Madonna capturing an enormous mainstream audience, has had a perhaps surprising impact in progressive circles.<ref name=\"GreenLeftWeekly\">{{cite news|url=https://www.greenleft.org.au/node/2766|title=and ain't i a woman?: Madonna: sexual revolutionary?|work=[[Green Left Weekly]]|last=Fredericks|first=Karen|date=October 22, 1992|issue=77|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Greta Gaard's article writes, \"Madonna's music videos enact the theory that gender is only one component of sexual identity-and a manipulpable one at that\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gaard|first=Greta|date=1992|title=The Laugh of Madonna: Censorship and Oppositional Discourse|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/1315073|journal=The Journal of the Midwest Modern Language Association|volume=25|issue=1|pages=41\u201346|doi=10.2307/1315073|issn=0742-5562}}</ref>\n\nArtists Adam Geczy and [[Vicki Karaminas]] in ''Queer Style'' (2013) noted Madonna transmogrified from virgin to dominatrix to ''\u00dcber Fran'', each time achieving iconic status. Added Madonna was the first woman to do so-and with mainstream panache and approbation.<ref name=\"Shaded2\">{{harvnb|Geczy|Karaminas|2013|p=38}}</ref> [[bell hooks]] teach that her \"power to the pussy\" credo worked only to solidify Madonna's positioning on the backs of the marginalized. The sexual icon she constructed may indeed, then, accord power to the pussy.<ref name=\"Shaded2\"/> Academics from [[European School of Management and Technology]] felt that Madonna became one of the world's first performers to manipulate the juxtaposition of sexual and religious themes.<ref name=\"ESMT\">{{cite news|url=http://www.esmt.org/fm/13/Madonna_article.pdf|title=Madonna \u2013 Strategy on the Dance Floor|publisher=[[European School of Management and Technology]] (ESMT)|year=2006|author=Jaime Anderson & Martin Kupp|accessdate=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529022945/http://www.esmt.org/fm/13/Madonna_article.pdf|archivedate=May 29, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> American editor [[Janice Min]] wrote that \"long before ''[[Sex and the City]]'', Madonna owned her sexuality. She made people cringe but also think differently about female performers. Her role as a provocateur changed boundaries for ensuing generations. She was a one-woman reality show.\"<ref name=\"USAToday\"/> As Min, Shmuel Boteach, author of ''Hating Women'' (2005), felt that Madonna was largely responsible for erasing the line between music and pornography. He stated: \"Before Madonna, it was possible for women more famous for their voices than their cleavage to emerge as music superstars. But in the post-Madonna universe, even highly original performers such as [[Janet Jackson]] now feel the pressure to expose their bodies on national television to sell albums\".<ref>{{harvnb|Boteach|2005|p=110}}</ref>\n\nDuring her career, Madonna has several provocative works. Perhaps, her book ''[[Sex (book)|Sex]]'' is most notorious, considered by many as the artist's most controversial and transgressive period.<ref name=\"Cambio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cambio.com.co/entretenimientocambio/791/ARTICULO-WEB-NOTA_INTERIOR_CAMBIO-4470108.html|title=Madonna, vigente a los 50|date=November 2, 2008|accessdate=February 21, 2013|language=Spanish|trans-title=Madonna, still got it at 50|publisher=Cambio.com ([[AOL]])|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515143201/http://www.cambio.com.co/entretenimientocambio/791/ARTICULO-WEB-NOTA_INTERIOR_CAMBIO-4470108.html|archivedate=May 15, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Some authors noted that ''Sex'' helped Madonna make a name in the [[porn industry]],<ref name=\"Kirk Davidson\"/> and earned her the title of [[Sadomasochism|S&M]]'s first [[cultural ambassador]].<ref name=\"Nyissue SM\">{{cite journal|date=November 18, 1994|title=S&M offers a safe haven for ex \"classy\" topless bars|journal=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|page=40|volume=27|issue=47|issn=0028-7369|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XeMCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA41}}</ref> Steve Bachmann, on his book ''Simulating Sex: Aesthetic Representations of Erotic Activity'' pointed out that \"perhaps one of the most interesting aspects of Madonna's sexual phenomenon is the extent to which her book marked a new threshold in the pornographic franchise\".<ref name=\"Bachman 2\">{{harvnb|Bachmann|2002|p=77}}</ref> Brian McNair, author of ''Striptease Culture: Sex, Media and the Democratisation of Desire'' (2012) praised this period of Madonna's career, saying that she had \"porno elegance\" and that \"''Sex'' is the author of a cultural phenomenon of global proportions [due to the critics] and thanks to this Madonna established her iconic status and cultural influence.<ref name=\"McNair267\">{{harvnb|McNair|2012|p=267}}</ref> Professors in ''Oh Fashion'' (1994) book felt that \"Madonna is a toy for boys, but on another level boys are toys for her\".<ref name=\"Oh\" />\n\n=== Queer and gay ===\n{{See also|Madonna as a gay icon}}\n[[File:Madonna Impersonator by David Shankbone.jpg|upright|thumb|LGBT [[Madonna wannabe|Madonna impersonator]].]]\n\nAccording to ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', Madonna is the greatest gay icon of all time.<ref name=\"Advocate\">{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/print-issue/cover-stories/2012/02/02/madonna-truth-she-never-left-you|title=Madonna: The Truth Is She Never Left You|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=February 2, 2012|accessdate=June 17, 2015|first=Ari|last=Karpel}}</ref> ''[[New Statesman]]'' reported that Madonna became the supreme gay icon, and the [[Madonna Studies]] analyzed and support these.<ref name=\"Statesman\">{{cite journal|title=Madonna|year=2000|accessdate=June 23, 2015|volume=129|issue= 4493\u20144505|work=[[New Statesman]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h_yFAAAAIAAJ&q=Madonna+a+gay+icon&dq=Madonna+a+gay+icon&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=eZ2JVZvTEIaYNovuk-AI&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAzge|page=46|ref=harv}}</ref> Scholars Carmine Sarracino and Kevin Scott in ''The Porning of America'' (2008), wrote that Madonna \"gained particular popularity with gay audiences, signaling the creation of a career-long fan base that would lead to her being hailed as the biggest gay icon of all time\".<ref>{{harvnb|Sarracino|Scott|2002|p=93}}</ref> ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' magazine wrote that Madonna \"stuck her neck out and positioned herself to be a gay icon before it was cool to be one\".<ref name=\"out\">{{cite journal|title=Your Letters continued|year=2005|accessdate=June 23, 2015|volume=13|issue=7\u201412|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=J_kiAQAAMAAJ&q=Madonna+is+a+gay+icon&dq=Madonna+is+a+gay+icon&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=aqyJVbLjGcKyggT8sZnABA&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAzgK|page=178|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n[[Associate professor]] Judith A. Peraino wrote that \"no one has worked harder to be a gay icon than Madonna, and she has done so by using every possible taboo sexual in her videos, performances, and interviews\".<ref>{{harvnb|Peraino|2005|p=143}}</ref> Similar, Alex Hopkins from ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' magazine denoted that gay community labeled her as [Their] 'Glorious Leader', \"Madge is part of our subculture's rich history of diva worship. She has referenced every sacred monster from Dietrich to Monroe, reveled in upfront, often transgressive sexuality and demonstrated a highly developed sense of camp. No wonder we loved her\". Also, her lack of inhibition helped inspire a generation of gay men and women to live on their own terms.<ref name=\"TimeOut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/lgbt/is-madonna-still-the-ultimate-gay-icon|title=Is Madonna still the ultimate gay icon?|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|date=August 11, 2011|accessdate=June 23, 2015|first=Alex|last=Hopkins}}</ref>\n\nMadonna is also referred to as a queer icon and icon of queerness. [[Theologist]], [[Robert Goss]] wrote: \"For me, Madonna has been not only a queer icon but also a Christ icon\".<ref>{{harvnb|Goss|2002|p=178}}</ref> Similar Sheila Whiteley from ''Sexing the Groove: Popular Music and Gender'' (2013) felt that \"Madonna came closer to any other contemporary celebrity in being an above-ground queer icon\".<ref>{{harvnb|Whiteley|2013|p=275}}</ref>\n\n=== Postmodern ===\nAccording to [[Lucy O'Brien]]: Much has been made of Madonna as a postmodern icon, yet all her reference points have been resolutely modernist\u2014from Steinbeck and Fitzgerald to Virginia Woolf and Sylvia Plath, to her predilection for narrative and psychoanalysis.<ref>{{harvnb|O'Brien|2007|p=27}}</ref>\n\nCanadian editor [[Richard Appignanesi]] wrote that for some \"Madonna is the cyber-model of the New Woman.<ref name=\"Appignanesi\">{{Harvnb|Appignanesi|Garratt|2014|p=}}</ref> Similar, [[senior lecturer]]s St\u00e9phanie Genz and Benjamin Brabon in ''Postfeminism: Cultural Texts and Theories'' (2009) felt that \"whether it is as a woman, mother, pop icon or fifty year old, the American singer challenges our preconceptions of who 'Madonna' is and, more broadly, what these identity categories mean within a postmodern context\".<ref>{{harvnb|Genz|Brabon|2009|p=118}}</ref>\n\n=== Pop icon and honorific nicknames and titles on popular culture ===\n{{see also|Honorific nicknames in popular music}}\nMadonna as a [[pop icon]] and figure on popular culture has generated scrutine analysis, but some journalists and critics like Carol Clerk wrote that \"during her career, Madonna has transcended the term 'pop star' to become a global cultural icon\".<ref name=\"culturalicontwo\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.m-magazine.co.uk/reviews/review-madonna-style/|title=Review: Madonna Style|work=[[M (magazine)|M]]|accessdate=June 18, 2015|date=November 12, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503083842/http://www.m-magazine.co.uk/reviews/review-madonna-style/|archivedate=May 3, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, academics from [[Rutgers University]] comments that \"Madonna has become the world's biggest and most socially significant pop icon, as well as the most controversial\".<ref name=\"Rutgers University\">{{cite web|url=http://dialogues.rutgers.edu/all-journals/volume-2/86-madonna-rebel-with-a-cause/file|title=MADONNA: REBEL WITH A CAUSE?|first=Duyen|last=Pham|publisher=[[Rutgers University]]|date=January 9, 2015|accessdate=June 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626123141/http://dialogues.rutgers.edu/all-journals/volume-2/86-madonna-rebel-with-a-cause/file|archive-date=June 26, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Critical theorist [[Douglas Kellner]] described her as \"a highly influential pop culture icon\" and \"the most discussed female singer in popular music\".<ref>{{harvnb|Kellner|1995|p=263}}</ref> Even, in 2012 Latin critics felt that Madonna is the most influential presence of current popular culture.<ref name=\"Totem\"/> Historian [[Jasmina Te\u0161anovi\u0107]] like others authors, noted that Madonna's changes are well-calculated in order to be ahead of the curve, of the game, to dictate the fashion, to be a trendsetter and called her as one of the most honest performers in pop culture.<ref name=\"Cleveland\"/> [[VH1]] listed her behind [[David Beckham]] as the greatest pop icon of all time.<ref name=\"Beckham\">{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/225856/becks-greatest-pop-icon-of-all-time|title=Becks: Greatest Pop Icon Of All Time|publisher=[[Sky News]]|location=United Kingdom|date=November 12, 2003|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliam Langley from ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' noted that Madonna \"remains a permanent fixture on every list of world's most powerful/admired/influential women.\"<ref name=\"list\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/madonna/8739518/Clear-the-set-Madonna-wants-to-express-herself.html|title=Clear the set \u2013 Madonna wants to express herself|last=Langley|first=William|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=September 3, 2011|accessdate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> For example, ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' listed her in the topping of \"the 50 female singers who will never be forgotten\".<ref name=\"Yahoo Brazil\">{{cite web|url=http://br.noticias.yahoo.com/s/080513/48/gjni65.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204230158/http://br.noticias.yahoo.com/s/080513/48/gjni65.html|title=As 50 cantoras que nunca ser\u00e3o esquecidas|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|location=Brazil|archivedate=February 4, 2010|accessdate=June 17, 2015|language=Portuguese}}</ref> American journalist [[Edna Gundersen]] felt that Madonna is \"durable pop [[triumvirate]]\".<ref name=\"USAToday\"/> Also, she has been referred to as a \"modern [[Medusa]]\" or \"queen of gender disorder and racial deconstruction\".<ref name=\"Kakutani\"/>\n\nMadonna has several titles, subjectives and superlatives, many of them explain and explore her large impact in many fields. Blogger Richard P\u00e9rez-Feria posted on ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' that \"over the course of her remarkable career, Madonna has been called many things... whore, which, for vastly different reasons. What Madonna ultimately achieved is nothing less than reigning as the universe's Queen of Pop, as in music, culture, life\".<ref name=\"Huffin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/richard-perezferia/madonna-the-worlds-bigges_b_5967112.html|title=Madonna: The World's Biggest Star Is Just Hitting Her Stride|work=[[HuffPost]]|date=October 10, 2014|accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref> Chilean newspaper of politics, economy and culture, ''[[:es:Qu\u00e9 Pasa|Qu\u00e9 Pasa]]'' stated in 1996, that \"to Madonna can be attributed many titles and never be exaggerated. She is the undisputed queen of pop, sex goddess, and of course marketing\".<ref name=\"Que\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ZrjAAAAMAAJ&q=Madonna+se+le+puede+atribuir+muchos&dq=Madonna+se+le+puede+atribuir+muchos&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=0ZqEVZ_xJMHMgwTkrIGgCg&ved=0CBMQ6AEwAA|title=Madonna|newspaper=[[:es:Qu\u00e9 Pasa|Qu\u00e9 Pasa]]|issue=1291-1303|year=1996|accessdate=June 18, 2015|page=513}}</ref> Music blogger [[Alan McGee]] from ''[[The Guardian]]'' felt that Madonna is post-modern art, the likes of which we will never see again. He further asserted that Madonna and [[Michael Jackson]] invented the terms [[Honorific nicknames in popular music|Queen and King of Pop]].<ref name=\"QueenandKing\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2008/oct/28/madonna-pop-art|title=Madonna Pop Art|first=Alan|last=McGee|authorlink=Alan McGee|newspaper=The Guardian|date=August 20, 2008|accessdate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> Like a corollary, her most notable nickname in world popular culture is Queen of Pop. Carlos Otero from [[Divinity (TV channel)|Divinity Channel]] wrote that \"Madonna has secured for life the title of Queen of Pop. He further asserted that \"after 30 years of career would take another three decades to meet her influence and legacy\".<ref name=\"Divinity\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.divinity.es/blogs/oteradas/Madonna-polemicas_6_1467465001.html|title=Madonna se aburguesa: sus pol\u00e9micas ya no son lo que eran|date=September 3, 2012|accessdate=June 21, 2013|last=Otero|first=Carlos|publisher=[[Divinity (TV channel)|Divinity TV]]|location=Spain|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nMathew Donahue, one of 12 faculty members of Bowling Green State University's [[Bowling Green State University Department of Popular Culture|Pop Culture Studies program]], gives lectures about Madonna in many of his music and culture classes has qualified her as the \"Queen of all Media\".<ref name=\"Cleveland\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/music/index.ssf/2013/08/30_years_of_madonna_how_the_qu.html|title=30 years of Madonna|first=Laura|last=DeMarco|publisher=[[The Plain Dealer|Cleveland]]|date=August 30, 2013|accessdate=June 13, 2015}}</ref> Also, she was named as the mother of \"kingdom technological\".<ref name=\"Lysloff\">{{harvnb|Lysloff|Gay|2003|pp=189\u2013192}}</ref> Madonna is also referred to as the Queen of MTV. [[CNN]] commented that [[MTV]] could stand for \"Madonna Television\".<ref name=\"CNNMTV\">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Music/9807/31/encore.mtv/|title=MTV changed the music industry on August 1, 1981|publisher=CNN|date=July 31, 1998|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> Jul\u00edan Ru\u00edz from Spanish newspaper ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'' said that she is our \"Lady Madonna\".<ref name=\"LadyMadonna\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/cultura/2013/11/19/528a313d6843415e3d8b4574.html|title=Santa Madonna, 'ora pro nobis'|trans-title=Holy Madonna, 'ora pro nobis'|first=Jul\u00edan|last=Ru\u00edz|work=El Mundo|location=Spain|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=June 20, 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n*The Queen<ref name=\"Muuse\">{{cite news|url=http://www.muumuse.com/2013/10/madonna-harpers-bazaar-november-2013-cover-secretprojectrevolution.html/|title=All Gold Everything: Madonna Covers November Issue of \u2018Harper\u2019s Bazaar\u2019|publisher=[[MuuMuse]]|date=October 3, 2013|last=Stern|first=Bradley|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n*Queen of Pop<ref name=\"QueenandKing\"/>\n*Queen of Videos<ref name=\"Nerdist\">{{cite web|url=http://nerdist.com/the-13-greatest-madonna-music-videos-of-all-time/|title=THE 13 GREATEST MADONNA MUSIC VIDEOS OF ALL TIME|date=February 8, 2015|accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher=[[Nerdist Industries]]|first=Eric|last=Diaz|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304194350/http://nerdist.com/the-13-greatest-madonna-music-videos-of-all-time/|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Landrum 2007 258\">{{harvnb|Landrum|2007|p=258}}</ref>\n*Queen of Concerts tours<ref name=\"NNN\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newnownext.com/the-re-invention-tours-30-years-of-madonna-live-in-concert/03/2015/|title=Re-Evolution: 30 Years Of Madonna In Concert|publisher=[[Logo TV|NewNowNext.com]]|date=March 4, 2015|author=Les Fabian Brathwaite|accessdate=June 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*Queen of MTV<ref name=\"Slant\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/features/article/2003-mtv-video-music-awards-recap|title=2003 MTV Video Music Awards: Recap|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=August 28, 2003|first=Sal|last=Cinquemani|accessdate=June 2, 2015}}</ref>\n*Queen of Reinvention<ref name=\"Landrum 2007 258\"/>\n*Queen of [[Billboard chart|''Billboard'' charts]]<ref name=\"Queenofcharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/499398/madonnas-40-biggest-billboard-hits|title=Madonna's the Queen of Charts|date=May 7, 2008|accessdate=March 7, 2015|work=Billboard|first=Wade|last=Jessen}}</ref>\n*Queen of Marketing<ref name=\"Que\"/>\n*Queen of all Media<ref name=\"Cleveland\"/>\n*Queen of Everything<ref name=\"QEthing\">{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2012/03/26/madonna-mdna-album-review/|title=\u2018MDNA\u2019 Track-By-Track Review: A Cheat Sheet To Madonna\u2019s New Album|date=March 26, 2012|accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher=MTV|first=Brad|last=Stern}}</ref>\n*Queen of the Obscene<ref name=\"Mirror\"/><ref name=\"Kirk Davidson\">{{Harvnb|Davidson|2003|p=100}}</ref>\n*Queen of Controversy<ref name=\"Qcontroversy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2014-11-19/madonna-most-controversial-instagram/|title=10 Reasons Madonna Is The Queen Of Controversy On Instagram|date=November 19, 2014|accessdate=June 23, 2015|publisher=VH1|first=Chris|last=Rosa}}</ref>\n*Queen of controversial music videos<ref name=\"Mirror\"/>\n*Goddess of Pop<ref name=\"Mehmet\"/>\n*Sex Goddess<ref name=\"Que\"/><ref name=\"Scripture Union\">{{Cite book|isbn=1844270327|title=Madonna: Materialism, Image, Family Relationships, Spirituality (Connect)|publisher=Amazon.com}}</ref>\n*Majesty<ref name=\"WMA\"/><ref name=\"Mirror\"/>\n*Dancing Queen<ref name=\"DancingQueen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/m/madonna/news_feature_051107/|title=Madonna: Dancing Queen|accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher=MTV|author=Jasmine Dotiwala, John Norris and Vanessa White Wolf}}</ref>\n*Material Girl<ref name=\"Mirror\"/>\n\n== Contradictory perspective ==\n[[File:Halloween-Parade feat. Madonna-Protest.jpg|left|thumb|A New Yorker protests Madonna adopting children from Africa on Halloween.]]\n\nProfessors in ''American Icons'' noted that she was not only an omnipresent figure but a [[Polarization (politics)|polarizing]] one. For example, in 1993, she was the subject of the ''I Hate Madonna Handbook'' and the following year the inspirations for ''I Dream of Madonna''.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{harvnb|Hall|2006|pp=446}}</ref> [[Lynn Spigel]] noted that Madonna is a producer of cultural ambiguity and openness.<ref name=\"Spiegel23\">{{harvnb|Spigel|2007|pp=123}}</ref> [[Rabbi]] Isaac Karudi \u2014the highest authority of the Orthodox [[Kabbalah]]\u2014 described her as a \"depraved [[cultural icon]]\".<ref name=\"ElMundo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/cronica/2004/461/1092757010.html|title=Los pecados que ya no cometer\u00e1s|last=Vidal|first=Jose Manuel|work=El Mundo|location=Spain|accessdate=April 15, 2015|language=Spanish}}</ref> Social critic and [[Critical theory|critical theorist]], [[Stuart Sim]] noted that \"Madonna now attained the status of cultural icon, she is however, an extremely problematic one, as her delight in simultaneously evoking and transgressing cultural stereotypes of feminity makes her exceedingly difficult to categorize; depending on one's point of view\".<ref name=\"Sim\">{{harvnb|Sim|2013|pp=310}}</ref> [[Cultural critic]] Fausto Rivera Y\u00e1nez from ''[[:es:El Tel\u00e9grafo|El Tel\u00e9grafo]]'' said that \"Madonna has labeling usurper, since much of its aesthetic and musical approach draws on religious imagery of [[African-American culture|black cultures]], discourses of [[sexual diversity]] and circumstantial [[Geopolitics|geopolitical]] contexts\".<ref name=\"ElTelegrafo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.telegrafo.com.ec/cultura/carton-piedra/item/madonna-quiero-controlar-el-mundo.html|title=Madonna: 'Quiero controlar el mundo'|trans-title=Madonna: 'I want to control the world'|last=Rivera Y\u00e1nez|first=Fausto|work=[[:es:El Tel\u00e9grafo|El Tel\u00e9grafo]]|location=Ecuador|date=September 16, 2013|accessdate=April 15, 2015|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924114114/http://www.telegrafo.com.ec/cultura/carton-piedra/item/madonna-quiero-controlar-el-mundo.html|archive-date=September 24, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Maureen Orth]] explain her the contradiction as a cultural and social impact:<ref name=\"Wonderland\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/1992/10/madonna199210|title=Madonna in Wonderland|date=October 1992|accessdate=April 17, 2015|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|authorlink=Maureen Orth|first=Maureen|last=Orth}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|quote=\"Madonna\u2019s celebrity is unique in that it seems to depend as much on repugnance as on acceptance. Her fame frame, unlike that of most other mega-stars, rests very much on people who love to hate her\u2014while monitoring her every move\u2014and on others who hate to love her, as well as on the traditional adoring fans. Perhaps it\u2019s not surprising that even academics are doing a brisk trade in 'Madonna-ology'.|source=}}\n\nAmerican [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning critic for ''[[The New York Times]]'' [[Michiko Kakutani]], felt that Madonna is incredibly popular. Or: \"Clearly, Madonna is not universally loved.\" Or: \"The politics of sex and gender representations as they relate to identity has not been lost on Madonna.\"<ref name=\"Kakutani\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/21/books/books-of-the-times-madonna-writes-academics-explore-her-erotic-semiotics.html|title=Books of The Times; Madonna Writes; Academics Explore Her Erotic Semiotics|date=October 21, 1992|accessdate=April 17, 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|authorlink=Michiko Kakutani|first=Michiko|last=Kakutani}}</ref> Authors in ''Representing gender in cultures'' (2004) noted that \"Madonna has been consistently denied a status of a 'real' musician and even accused of using, in a vampire-like way, fashionable musicians to update her sound\".<ref name=\"criticmusic\">{{cite book|last1=H. Oleksy|first1=El\u017cbieta|first2=Joanna|last2=Rydzewska|title=Representing gender in cultures|year=2004|accessdate=June 22, 2015|isbn=3631506678|publisher=[[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]]|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WaRhAAAAMAAJ&q=Madonna+has+been+consistently+denied+a+status+of+a+%22real%22+musician+and+even+accused+of+using,+in+a+vampire-like+way,+fashionable+musicians+to+update+her+sound&dq=Madonna+has+been+consistently+denied+a+status+of+a+%22real%22+musician+and+even+accused+of+using,+in+a+vampire-like+way,+fashionable+musicians+to+update+her+sound&hl=es-419&sa=X&ei=2sSIVYWkC8GkNsXPv6gO&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAA|page=134|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nDuring her career, Madonna attracted the attention of family organizations, feminist \"[[Opposition to pornography|anti-porn]]\" and religious groups worldwide with boycott and protests. Professor Bruce David Forbes author of ''Religion and Popular Culture in America'' (2005) felt that \"some of the most important and interesting texts in recent American culture which have overlapping concerns with liberation theologies are by Madonna\".<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{harvnb|Forbes|2005|pp=75}}</ref> Karen Fredericks from socialist newspaper ''[[Green Left Weekly]]'' questioned if does the \"Madonna phenomenon\" advance the cause of women's liberation within [[Western societies]]? she said that clearly, there's no point going to Madonna for help. She asserted that the artist is a commodity in a [[capitalist]] market which has been influenced, at least to some extent, by the demands of the women's movement.<ref name=\"GreenLeftWeekly\"/> Sociologist John Shepherd wrote that Madonna's cultural practices highlight the sadly continuing social realities of dominance and subordination.<ref name=\"john\" /> In 1988, one Italian sculptor planned a statue of Madonna in [[Pacentro]], where are from her paternal grandparents, who said \"Madonna is a symbol of our children and represents a better world in the year 2000\". The then mayor of the city declared: \"it is absolutely untrue that the city administration of Pacentro is willing to host the statue to the singer Madonna as some maintain\".<ref name=\"Statue\">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/1988-01-06/news/26284162_1_e-streeters-dates-and-venues-honorary-citizen|title=Statue Of Madonna Is Debated|date=January 6, 1988|accessdate=June 17, 2015|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]]|author=W. Speers}}</ref><ref name=\"StatueAP\">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.philly.com/1988-01-06/news/26284162_1_e-streeters-dates-and-venues-honorary-citizen|title=Statue of Madonna won't stand in Italy|date=January 8, 1988|accessdate=June 17, 2015|work=[[The Gettysburg Times]]|author=[[Associated Press]] (AP)}}</ref>\n\nAcademic Audra Gaugler from [[Lehigh University]] advocated for Madonna, wrote that \"she has faced much criticism throughout her career, but much of it is unjust. Instead of Madonna's actions eliciting criticism, they should elicit praise because she radically tries to change society by blurring the boundaries that separate different groups of people in society and she urges all people to gain power in their lives and lift themselves out of subordinate positions. Madonna blurs the boundaries that exist in society and separate people in society in two distinct ways\". She noted that there exists a large band of critics that at first praised her, but then became disillusioned with her as she became more and more controversial.<ref name=\"Gaugler\">{{Cite news|url=http://preserve.lehigh.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1662&context=etd|title=Madonna, an American pop icon of feminism and counter-hegemony : blurring the boundaries &#91;sic&#93; of race, gender, and sexuality by Audra Gaugler.|year=2000|accessdate=June 18, 2015|publisher=[[Lehigh University]]|first=Audra|last=Gaugler}}</ref>\n\n== Sources ==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{Cite book\n |last = Appignanesi\n |first = Richard\n |first2 = Chris\n |last2 = Garratt\n |authorlink=Richard Appignanesi\n |title = Introducing Postmodernism: A Graphic Guide\n |publisher = Icon Books\n |isbn = 1848317603\n |year = 2014\n |ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n |first=Marcela\n |last= Aguilar Guzm\u00e1n\n |title=Domadores de historias. Conversaciones con grandes cronistas de Am\u00e9rica Latina\n |publisher=RIL Editores\n |year=2010\n |isbn=956-284-782-9\n |language=Spanish\n |ref=harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n |last = Barcella\n |first = Laura\n |title = Madonna and Me: Women Writers on the Queen of Pop\n |publisher = [[Soft Skull Press]]\n |year = 2012\n |isbn = 1-59376-475-8\n |ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n |last2 = Metz\n |first2 = Allen\n |first = Carol\n |last = Benson\n |title = The Madonna Companion: Two Decades of Commentary\n |publisher = [[Music Sales Group]]\n |year = 1999\n |isbn = 0-8256-7194-9\n |ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n | last = Benson\n | first = Carol\n | title = Madonna the Companion Two Decades of Commentary\n | publisher = Music Sales Group\n | year = 2000\n | isbn = 0825671949\n | ref = harv\n }}\n*{{Cite book\n |last1 = Benstock\n |first1 = Shari\n |last2 = Ferriss\n |first2 = Suzanne\n |title = Oh Fashion\n |publisher = [[Rutgers University Press]]\n |year = 1994\n |isbn = 0813520339\n |ref = harv\n |url = https://archive.org/details/onfashion00pect\n }}\n*{{Cite book\n |last = Boteach\n |first = Shmuel\n |title = Hating women: America's hostile campaign against the fairer sex\n |publisher = [[HarperCollins]]\n |year = 2005\n |isbn = 978-0-06-078122-4\n |ref = harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n |last1 = Blackmore\n |first1 = Hazel\n |last2 = de Castro\n |first2 = Rafael Fern\u00e1ndez\n |title = \u00bfQu\u00e9 es Estados Unidos?\n |publisher = [[Fondo de Cultura Economica]]\n |year = 2008\n |isbn = 97