 News, LGBT Rights, Politics, Entertainment}}</ref> ''[[HuffPost]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/michael-lucas |title=Michael Lucas |publisher=huffingtonpost.com |date= |accessdate=2012-01-17}}</ref> and ''[[Pink News]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/author/michael-lucas/ |title=Michael Lucas Pink UK columns |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[The New Republic|New Republic]]'' dubbed Lucas \"Gay Porn's Neocon Kingpin\",<ref name=\"Kerchik\">[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/03/20/opinion/main3954850.shtml Gay Porn's Neocon Kingpin], James Kirchick, ''The New Republic'' via CBSNews.com, March 20, 2006.</ref> and ''[[FrontPage Magazine]]'' cited him as \"the most mainstreamed, provocative, and controversial figure in gay adult entertainment today.\"<ref>[http://frontpagemag.com/2011/05/13/michael-lucas-a-gay-man-for-israel/ Michael Lucas: A Gay Man For Israel] {{Webarchive|url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120302184106/http://frontpagemag.com/2011/05/13/michael-lucas-a-gay-man-for-israel/ |date=March 2, 2012 }}, Jamie Glazov, ''[[FrontPage Magazine]]'', May 13, 2011; accessed July 18, 2011.</ref> He contends that his film ''[[Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita]]'' is the most expensive [[gay pornography|gay porn]] film ever made, with a budget of $250,000 and multiple celebrity [[Cameo appearance|cameos]].<ref name=\"Van Meter\" /> In 2009, Lucas was inducted into the [[GayVN]] Hall of Fame, noted for \"his stature as an A-list director and performer\".<ref name=\"fame\">[http://business.avn.com/articles/GAYVN-Announces-2009-Hall-of-Fame-Inductees-307129.html GAYVN Announces 2009 Hall of Fame Inductees], Harker Jones, AVN, March 12, 2009.</ref> He was included in a 2009 ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine feature about people who made it to the top, but arrived to the city with very little.<ref name=\"top\">[https://nymag.com/news/features/56014/ Waking Up to New York] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401105356/http://nymag.com/news/features/56014/index6.html |date=April 1, 2012 }}, ''[[New York Magazine]]'', April 10, 2009.</ref>\n\nLucas is particularly well known for his activism and outspokenness.<ref name=\"Van Meter\" /><ref name=\"Kerchik\" /><ref name=\"fame\" /> His criticism of [[recreational drug use|drug use]] and his sponsorship of public service [[ad campaign]]s about the dangers of [[unprotected sex]] in the [[gay community]] led [[Harvey Fierstein]] to interview him for ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]''.<ref name=\"advocate\" /> His ''[[New York Blade]]'' columns on [[Ultra-Orthodox Judaism]] and [[Islam]] sparked a campus debate at [[Stanford University]] in February 2008 when Lucas was invited to give a speech to students.<ref name=\"Stan1\" /> In 2010 he debated [[Peter Tatchell]] and [[Sue Sanders]] at England's [[Oxford University]] on whether the gay rights movement has undermined [[family values]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/features/view/177376/Porn-actor-Michael-Lucas-to-speak-at-Oxford-University%20Porn-actor-Michael-Lucas-to-speak-at-Oxford-UniversityPorn-actor-Michael-Lucas-to-speak-at-Oxford-University |title=Porn Actor Michael Lucas To Speak at Oxford University |publisher=Express.co.uk |date=May 27, 2010 |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lucas released the film ''[[Men of Israel]]'', which he called his most important.  Journalists from ''[[The Atlantic]]'', ''[[Out Magazine]]'' and ''[[Yediot Aharonot]]'' noted it as a landmark film as the first pornographic movie shot on location with an all-[[Israelis|Israeli]] cast;<ref name=\"Tablet\">[http://www.tabletmag.com/life-and-religion/10955/great-exxxpectations/ Great Exxxpectations], Wayne Hoffman, Tablet Magazine, July 21, 2009.</ref> while ''[[Tablet Magazine]]'' and the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' remarked on it being the first to feature an all-[[Jewish]] cast.<ref name=\"Tablet\" /><ref name=\"Newsweek\">[http://www.newsweek.com/blogs/wealth-of-nations/2009/09/23/gay-porn-mogul-hopes-to-arouse-interest-in-israel.html Gay-Porn Mogul Hopes to Arouse Interest in Israel], David Graham, ''[[Newsweek]]'', September 23, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"DNA\">[http://dnamagazine.com.au/articles/news.asp?news_id=8963 First-Ever All-Israeli Gay Porn Movie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511100125/http://www.dnamagazine.com.au/articles/news.asp?news_id=8963 |date=May 11, 2009 }}, ''DNA'' magazine, May 9, 2009.</ref> Lucas followed the film with a gay tour of Israel.<ref>{{cite web|last=Contributors |first=Advocate |url=http://www.advocate.com/Print_Issue/Travel/Michael_Lucas_Wants_to_Take_You_to_Israel/ |title=Michael Lucas Wants to Take You To Israel |publisher=Advocate.com |date=March 9, 2010 |accessdate=2014-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313154613/http://www.advocate.com/Print_Issue/Travel/Michael_Lucas_Wants_to_Take_You_to_Israel/ |archivedate=March 13, 2010 }}</ref> New York's [[Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual & Transgender Community Center|LGBT Center]] stopped allowing groups associated with the [[Israeli-Palestinian conflict]] to meet in their building after Lucas led a protest over their allowance of an [[Opposition in the United States to the Israeli occupation|anti-occupation]] group.\n\nIn recent years Lucas has also begun work as a documentarian.<ref>Huffington Post | Porn Magnate Michael Lucas To Release Documentary About Being Gay In Russia (VIDEO) | http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/02/20/michael-lucas-documentary-gay-russia_n_4816848.html</ref> In 2012, he released his first documentary film about the thriving Israeli LGBT community. Titled ''[[Undressing Israel: Gay Men in the Promised Land]]'',<ref name=\"haaretz\">{{cite news |url= http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/culture-fop/culture-fop-don-t-worry-israel-the-king-of-gay-porn-is-behind-you.premium-1.502747 |author= Brian Schaefer |title= Culture Fop / Don't worry, Israel, the king of gay porn is behind you |publisher= Haaretz (in English) |date= February 11, 2013 |accessdate= 2016-10-07 }}</ref> the film includes footage of Tel Aviv's vibrant nightlife, a same-sex wedding, and candid interviews with a diverse range of local Israeli gays and lesbians, including a gay MP, an openly gay Army trainer, a drag queen, a transvestite, a young Arab-Israeli journalist, and same-sex parents raising their children and a number of artists and activists. In 2014 Lucas released his second documentary, \"Campaign of Hate: Russia and Gay Propaganda,\" which investigates the current anti-gay climate in Russian  politics and society.<ref>Breaking Glass Pictures | Campaign of Hate: Russia and Gay Propaganda | http://bgpics.com/index.php/template-styles/new-releases/item/235-campaign-of-hate {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624151622/http://bgpics.com/index.php/template-styles/new-releases/item/235-campaign-of-hate |date=June 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nLucas was born in 1972 in Moscow, Russia, to Lev Bregman, an engineer, and Elena Treivas, a [[Russian literature]] teacher. He was raised in a secular [[Jew]]ish family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-215_162-3954850.html|title=Gay Porn's Neocon Kingpin|accessdate=2012-05-02|publisher=[[CBS]]|date=September 22, 2009}}</ref> In 1994 he obtained a [[academic degree|degree]] in law from [[Kutafin Moscow State Law University]].<ref name=\"Lucas bio\" /><ref name=\"gaypornblog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gaypornblog.com/archives/2005/06/michael_lucas_t.html |title=Michael Lucas: The Gay Porn Blog Interview |accessdate=2007-01-10 |publisher=gaypornblog |date=June 19, 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070309012751/http://www.gaypornblog.com/archives/2005/06/michael_lucas_t.html |archivedate=March 9, 2007 }}</ref> After graduation, Lucas briefly owned and operated a [[travel agency]] in Russia until 1995.\n\nIn 1995, Lucas left for [[Munich]], Germany, on a tourist visa. Without an official work permit,<ref>[https://www.edgemedianetwork.com/entertainment/celebrities//167566 Michael Lucas: The Polarizing Prince of Porn] edgemedianetwork.com, 28 October 2014</ref> Lucas worked and starred in heterosexual porn.<ref name=\"advocate.com\">[https://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/people/2013/08/06/22-russians-who-we-wont-let-vladimir-putin-forget-were-gay?pg=13&fb_comment_id=553698391332606_5432651 22 Russians Who We Won't Let Vladimir Putin Forget Were LGBT] advocate.com, 06 August 2013</ref> He then worked as a nude model and in gay porn for French adult film producer [[Jean-Daniel Cadinot]] in Paris, outstaying his tourist visa.<ref>[http://depesha.com/arts-culture/culture/michaellucas What\u2019s Adult about Michael Lucas? Porn, Politics & Profits] depesha.com, 07 August 2013</ref><ref name=\"Butt\">[http://www.buttmagazine.com/magazine/interviews/michael-lucas/ Michael Lucas New York's Hardcore Porn Director From Russia Eats Ass in Private], Gert Jonkers, ''[[Butt Magazine]]''</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Lucas moved to New York City by invitation of a Wall Street businessman he had met in Munich.<ref name=\"top\" /> In New York, he worked at the [[Gaiety Theatre, New York (male burlesque)|Gaiety Theater]].<ref>[https://www.queerty.com/act-i-scene-i-michael-lucas-arrives-in-new-york-20090417 Act I, Scene I: Michael Lucas Arrives in New York] queerty.com, 17 April 2009</ref><ref name=\"Lucas bio\">[http://www.lucasentertainment.com/models.asp?ModelID=12 Model profile] at www.lucasentertainment.com, retrieved from www.lucasentertainment.com on September 5, 2006</ref><ref name=\"Oswoski\">Oswoski, Kevin (April 22, 2005), {{cite web|url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/14236 |title=Adult film producer fleshes out his 'fantasy' at tea |accessdate=2007-01-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217165954/http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/14236 |archivedate=December 17, 2007 }}, ''Yale Daily News'', retrieved from www.yaledailynews.com on August 31, 2006.</ref> After a few adult industry jobs in California, he was offered a one-year contract by [[Falcon Entertainment]] whose producers had seen him in a French Cadinot film. Lucas won a [[Lawful permanent residents (United States)|U.S. green card]] through the [[Diversity Immigrant Visa|lottery system]].<ref>[https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9bzqzp/body-of-an-american-0000320-v21n5 The Immigrant Who Conquered Porn and Became One of the Most Powerful Gay Men in New York] vice.com, 03 June 2014</ref> With money saved from his work at Falcon, Lucas founded his own gay porn company in New York, rather than Los Angeles where most American porn companies are headquartered, in 1998.\n\nIn 2001, Lucas brought his Russian family to the United States.<ref>[https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2013/08/russian-gays-talk-homosexual-propaganda-law.html Russian Gays Talk \u2018Homosexual Propaganda\u2019 and Life in New York] nymag.com, 15 August 2013</ref> His parents have since then returned to Moscow. On November 12, 2004, Lucas was sworn in as an American [[Citizenship|citizen]].<ref name=\"Lucas bio\" /> In October 2008 it was announced that Lucas had married his boyfriend of eight years, Richard Winger.<ref name=\"Gawk\">\"[http://gawker.com/5064078/gay-porn-impresario-michael-lucas-married Gay Porn Impresario Michael Lucas, Married] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327214953/http://gawker.com/5064078/gay-porn-impresario-michael-lucas-married |date=March 27, 2009 }}\". [[Gawker.com]]. October 15, 2008.</ref> A press release stated that the couple wanted to get married to make a statement about [[same-sex marriage]] rights.<ref name=\"Gawk\" /> In 2014 Lucas announced he and Winger divorced.<ref>Vice: Body of an American -- The Russian Immigrant Who Conquered Porn (https://www.vice.com/read/body-of-an-american-0000320-v21n5)</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Actor ===\nLucas began his career in a German heterosexual [[pornographic film]].<ref name=\"Oswoski\" /> While in France, he worked under the influential French director [[Jean-Daniel Cadinot]],<ref>Dunn, Rick (April 27, 2005), [http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=entertainment&sc=movies&sc2=features&sc3=&id=495 \"Down and Dirty With Michael Lucas\"], retrieved from www.edgeboston.com on January 16, 2007</ref> appearing as \"Ramzes Kairoff\" in two gay pornographic films, both released in 1996.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} Using the name \"Michel Lucas,\" he worked as a [[Falcon Studios|Falcon Exclusive]], performing as a [[top (sex)|top]] in five films released in 1997 and 1998.<ref>List of videos at the {{cite web |url=http://www.falconstudios.com/shop/showBiggerList.do?websiteName=falconstore&searchResults=true&searchTopic=Michel+Lucas&sectionName=shop_default&groupName=shop_default |title=Falcon Studio |access-date=September 10, 2016}} online store with Michel Lucas in the cast. ''Adult images.'' Retrieved from www.falconstudios.com on September 3, 2006</ref>\n\n=== Director ===\nHe directed his first project, ''Back in the Saddle'', in 1998, and also performed in the film.<ref name=\"Adam 1999\">{{cite book\n| editor-last = Lawrence\n| editor-first = Doug\n| authorlink = | year = 1998\n| title = Adam Gay Video 1999 Directory\n| publisher = Knight Publishing Corp.\n| location = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| id = }}</ref> With co-director Tony DiMarco, Lucas won Best Director at the 2007 [[GayVN]] Awards for ''[[Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita]]''.  DiMarco and Lucas also won a 2008 [[XBIZ]] Award for Best GLBT Director, and Lucas received an award for Best Publicity Stunt for \"Michael Lucas Found Dead\".<ref name=\"Xbiz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xbizawards.com/winners.php |title=X Biz Award Winners |publisher=Xbizawards.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Banana Guide'' called his productions the most polished, big-budget gay porn films ever made and cited Lucas' love for the subject and high technical aptitude.<ref name=\"Banana\">[http://bananaguide.com/article/75955 Review of Lucas Entertainment], ''The Banana Guide'', June 2009.</ref>\n\n== Lucas Entertainment ==\n{{main|Lucas Entertainment}}\nIn 1998, Lucas founded his own production company, [[Lucas Entertainment (Studio)|Lucas Entertainment]].<ref name=\"Oswoski\" /> He based the company in New York City (rather than Los Angeles, where many of the other [[List of pornographic movie studios|pornography studios]] are located in part because of the city's hospitable environment for adult films.)<ref name=\"Mao\">Mao, Tien (June 21, 2006),[http://gothamist.com/2006/06/21/michael_lucas_c.php Michael Lucas, CEO Lucas Entertainment] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308011640/http://gothamist.com/2006/06/21/michael_lucas_c.php |date=March 8, 2009 }}, retrieved December 18, 2006 from www.gothamist.com</ref> In 2004, Lucas Distribution, Inc., his adult video distribution company, began operations.  Lucas directs, produces and stars in his own films under the Lucas Entertainment banner. His studio has garnered many [[GayVN Awards]]<ref name=\"edgeboston.com\">{{cite web|last=Israel |first=Robert |url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ci=108&ch=news&sc=glbt&sc2=news&sc3=&id=18431 |title=Michael Lucas' 'La Dolce Vita' Sets GAYVN Record |publisher=Edgeboston.com |date=February 26, 2007 |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref> and [[Adult Erotic Gay Video Awards]] (\"Grabbys\") nominations and wins{{Citation needed|date=September 2007}}.\n\nIn the summer of 2005 Lucas released ''[[Michael Lucas' Dangerous Liaisons]]''; the film featured celebrity cameos from [[RuPaul]], [[Boy George]], [[Graham Norton]], [[Bruce Vilanch]], [[Lady Bunny]], [[Amanda Lepore]], and [[Michael Musto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0834930/plotsummary|title=The Making of Michael Lucas' 'Dangerous Liaisons' (Video 2006)}}</ref>\n\nThe company received 24 nominations for the 2009 [[GayVN]] Awards, including best picture for ''Return to Fire Island''.  That May, Lucas filmed the first gay porn film using all Israeli models, billing it as a sexual journey to promote Israeli culture.<ref name=\"Gawk2\">\"[http://gawker.com/5245068/sensitive-gay-porn-technology-smuggled-to-israel Sensitive Gay Porn Technology Smuggled to Israel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615041240/http://gawker.com/5245068/sensitive-gay-porn-technology-smuggled-to-israel |date=June 15, 2009 }}\". Ryan Tate, ''Gawker''. May 8, 2009.</ref> The company launched its ''Men of Israel'' website to promote the film, which announced its release for July 22.\n\n=== Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita ===\n\n{{main|Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita}}\nIn 2006, the studio released ''[[Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita]] Parts 1 & 2'', a [[gay pornography|gay pornographic]] [[remake]] of the 1960 [[Federico Fellini|Fellini]] classic ''[[La Dolce Vita]]''.<ref name=\"tla\">List of credits at the [http://www.tlavideo.com/gay-michael-lucas/person-31198-3 tlavideo] online video store, retrieved from www.tlavideo.com January 9, 2007</ref> The film won a record fourteen awards at the 2007 [[GayVN Awards]], winning in every category in which it was nominated.<ref name=\"edgeboston.com\" />\n\nIn February 2007, International Media Films, Inc., which owns the [[property|rights]] to Fellini's ''La Dolce Vita'', filed [[lawsuit|suit]] against Lucas (as Andrei Treivas Bregman), Lucas Entertainment, Inc., and Lucas Distribution, Inc. for [[trademark infringement|trademark]] and [[copyright infringement]].<ref>{{cite journal| date=February 15, 2007 | title=Copy of Complaint| journal=Online.WSJ.com/Public/Resources/Documents |url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/021507ladolce.pdf}}</ref>  The lawsuit seeks to collect unspecified [[damages]] and to stop sales of ''Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita Parts 1 & 2''.<ref>{{cite journal | date=April 27, 2007 |title=Transcript of judge's ruling| journal=Online.WSJ.com/Public/Resources/Documents | url=https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/lucas0505.pdf}}</ref>\n\nLucas won the lawsuit in April 2010 in a [[summary judgment]] by Judge John George Koeltl, who dismissed IMF's claims of copyright infringement, since many porn films have parodied mainstream films.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rubinkam |first=Michael |url=http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=&sc2=features&sc3=&id=104679 |title=Edge Boston April 2010 article about lawsuit |publisher=Edgeboston.com |date=April 19, 2010 |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\n== Writer, speaker and activist ==\n{{rquote|right|''I couldn't talk about anything in Russia. I was growing up in a very strict regime. But I rebelled.''|'''Michael Lucas'''<ref name=\"Musto\" />}}\nIn the 2000s, Lucas attracted attention for his views on politics and culture through a series of columns, speaking events and his increasing activism.  He is a vocal opponent of drug use and an advocate for [[safe sex]], both in the porn industry and the gay community at large.  In August 2004, ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' published an interview by [[Harvey Fierstein]] with Lucas about his full-page [[public service announcement]]s in several national publications warning of the dangers of unprotected sex.<ref name=\"advocate\">{{cite journal\n  | last = Kennedy\n  | first = Sean\n  | authorlink =\n  | title = Porn star wants you ... safe\n  | journal = Advocate.com Planet Out Inc.\n  | volume = 920\n  | issue = 37\u201339\n  | pages = 37\u201339\n  | date = August 17, 2004\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | issn = 0001-8996}}</ref>\n\nIncreasingly Lucas gained attention for his politics, and in particular his views on Israel and Muslims. In March 2008 he was profiled in ''[[The New Republic]]'' as \"Gay porn's neocon kingpin\".  The article explored his background and a controversy over his writings on [[Islam]] that surrounded a lecture he gave at [[Stanford University]].<ref name=\"Kerchik\" />\n\nIn an interview with [[Michael Musto]] in April 2009, Lucas remarked that his stifled upbringing in [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Soviet Russia]] influenced how vocal he is about his opinions.<ref name=\"Musto\">[http://www.villagevoice.com/2009-04-22/columns/the-naked-truth-about-porn-prince-michael-lucas/2 The Naked Truth about Michael Lucas], [[Michael Musto]], ''[[The Village Voice]]'', April 21, 2009</ref>\n\nLucas wrote about the need for LGBT people to reassess conservatives in August 2010, citing [[Ann Coulter]] as an example of a gay-friendly conservative leader.<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/Politics/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_It_Takes_a_Coulter/ It Takes a Coulter] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120716143740/http://www.advocate.com/Politics/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_It_Takes_a_Coulter/ |date=July 16, 2012 }}, Michael Lucas, ''The Advocate'', August 24, 2010; accessed July 18, 2011</ref> One month later he attended the [[GOProud]] 2010 convention, where he argued with Coulter about the perception of her anti-gay jokes among the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party's]] base voters.<ref>[http://blogs.villagevoice.com/dailymusto/2010/09/michael_lucas_v.php Michael Lucas vs. Ann Coulter], [[Michael Musto]], ''[[The Village Voice]]''; September 28, 2010; accessed July 18, 2011</ref>\n\n=== Columnist ===\nOn April 20, 2007, ''[[New York Blade|The New York Blade]]'' began to publish regular opinion columns by Lucas, who had previously had a number of comments published in the Blade's opinion section.<ref>{{cite journal| date=April 20, 2007|author=Michael Lucas | title=When gays don't attack |journal=[[New York Blade]]|url=http://nyblade.com/2007/4-20/viewpoint/opinion/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026094626/http://nyblade.com/2007/4-20/viewpoint/opinion/|archivedate=October 26, 2007| format=}}</ref> In October 2009, Lucas wrote a column for ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' decrying the group Queers Undermining Israeli Terrorism.<ref name=\"Advocate2\">[http://www.advocate.com/Politics/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_Queers_for_Palestine_/ Queers for Palestine?], Michael Lucas, ''The Advocate'', October 5, 2009.</ref> In March 2010 Lucas began writing a column for ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]''.  His columns have focused on Israel,<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/Society/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_Europes_Trouble_with_Israel/ Europe's Trouble with Israel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101026151435/http://advocate.com/Society/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_Europes_Trouble_with_Israel/ |date=October 26, 2010 }}, Michael Lucas, ''The Advocate''</ref> Russia's confronting homosexuality,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lucas |first=Michael |url=http://www.advocate.com/Politics/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_Russias_Struggle_to_Demonstrate_Pride/ |title=Russia's Struggle to Demonstrate Pride |publisher=Advocate.com |date=May 30, 2010 |accessdate=2014-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111220022700/http://www.advocate.com/Politics/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_Russias_Struggle_to_Demonstrate_Pride/ |archivedate=December 20, 2011 }}</ref> and the [[Park51]] controversy.<ref>[http://www.advocate.com/Society/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_The_Monument_to_Muslim_Terrorism/ The Monument to Muslim Terrorism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101026151540/http://advocate.com/Society/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_The_Monument_to_Muslim_Terrorism/ |date=October 26, 2010 }}.</ref> In 2011 he started writing a column for Huffington Post.\n\n==== Islam ====\nHis writings on [[Islam]] have been controversial.<ref>{{cite journal| date=June 1, 2007|author=Faisal Alam | title=Fanning Flames of Fear, Hatred Against Muslims |journal=[[New York Blade]]|url=http://nyblade.com/2007/6-1/viewpoint/opinion/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070604163015/http://nyblade.com/2007/6-1/viewpoint/opinion/|archivedate=June 4, 2007| format=}}</ref> In a 2007 ''[[New York Blade]]'' column, Lucas expressed support for artist Charles Merrill's burning of a Koran that was estimated at $60,000.<ref name=\"Kerchik\" /><ref name=\"Burn Koran\">{{cite journal| date=August 3, 2007|author=Michael Lucas | title=Burn the Koran? It's Gay Artwork |journal=[[New York Blade]]|url=http://nyblade.com/2007/8-3/viewpoint/opinion/koran.cfm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504040319/http://nyblade.com/2007/8-3/viewpoint/opinion/koran.cfm|archivedate=May 4, 2008| format= \u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ABurn+the+Koran%3F+It%E2%80%99s+Gay+Artwork&as_publication=%5B%5BNew+York+Blade%5D%5D&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|date=August 3, 2007 |author=Michael Lucas |title=Religion, Sexuality, and Art |journal=World Congress of Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual, and Transgender Jews |url=http://www.glbtjews.org/article.php3?id_article=482 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070918014809/http://www.glbtjews.org/article.php3?id_article=482 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 18, 2007 }}</ref>  He has condemned Islam and accused it of creating negative attitudes that lead to the persecution of homosexuals and discrimination of women.\n\nAs a columnist for ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', Lucas continued to explore Islamic topics.  In a heavily debated column,<ref name=\"Edge\">[http://www.edgeboston.com/index.php?ch=news&sc=&sc3=&id=111138 Should We Be Defending Islam, Despite Its Homophobia?], Joseph Erbentraut, Edge Boston, October 5, 2010; accessed July 27, 2011</ref> he called the [[Cordoba House]], a proposed Islamic community center and mosque controversially located near the [[World Trade Center site]], a 'monument to Muslim terrorism' and an example of \"political Islam's ascendancy.\"<ref name=\"Monument\">[http://www.advocate.com/Society/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_The_Monument_to_Muslim_Terrorism/ The Monument to Muslim Terrorism] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101026151540/http://advocate.com/Society/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_The_Monument_to_Muslim_Terrorism/ |date=October 26, 2010 }}, Michael Lucas, ''The Advocate'', August 9, 2010; accessed July 27, 2011</ref> After the [[2011 Egyptian revolution]] he wrote that the [[Muslim Brotherhood]] would fill a power vacuum, asserting that it would be a problem for the discreet [[LGBT rights in Egypt|Egyptian gay community]] that has lived with relatively little government persecution.<ref name=\"Egypt\">[http://www.advocate.com/Society/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_Myth_of_Democracy_in_Egypt/ Democracy in Egypt a Myth?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611025834/http://www.advocate.com/Society/Commentary/Michael_Lucas_on_Myth_of_Democracy_in_Egypt/ |date=June 11, 2011 }}, Michael Lucas, ''The Advocate'', January 31, 2011; accessed July 27, 2011</ref>\n\n=== University lectures ===\nIn April 2005, Lucas was invited to speak before a [[Calhoun College]] Master's Tea at [[Yale University]]. The speech was organized with the assistance of gaYalies, a campus group for gay and [[bisexual]] men.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yale.edu/lgbt/gayalies.html |title=GAYalies |date=February 2, 2009 |accessdate=2014-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001209231600/http://www.yale.edu/lgbt/gayalies.html |archivedate=December 9, 2000 }}</ref> He spoke about his life history and his views on pornography.<ref name=\"Oswoski\" /> In February 2006 he participated in a [[symposium]] on adult entertainment that was sponsored by the ''Yale Journal of Law and Feminism'', which later published Lucas' discussion in its Spring issue.<ref>{{cite journal\n| last = Lucas\n| first = Michael\n| authorlink = | title = On Gay Porn\n| journal = Yale Journal of Law and Feminism\n| volume = 18\n| issue = 299\n| pages = | date = Spring 2006\n| url = | doi = | id = | accessdate = }}</ref>\n\nThe Speakers Bureau at [[Stanford University]] invited Lucas to speak in Cubberley Auditorium on February 14, 2008, about the role the adult entertainment industry plays in AIDS prevention.<ref name=\"Stan1\">{{cite web|url=http://daily.stanford.edu/article/2008/2/14/adultFilmStarsRemarksSparkDebate |title=Adult film star's remarks spark debate |accessdate=2009-10-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216000624/http://daily.stanford.edu/article/2008/2/14/adultFilmStarsRemarksSparkDebate |archivedate=February 16, 2008 }}, Kelly Fong, February 14, 2008, ''[[The Stanford Daily]]''.</ref> The appearance sparked debate about his political columns for the ''[[New York Blade]]'', particularly his assertions that \"the [[Qur'an]] is today's ''[[Mein Kampf]]''\" and that its teachings inspire [[Muslims]] to kill [[gay people]].<ref name=\"Stan1\" />\n\nLucas, who grew up in the [[Soviet Union]] and experienced its [[Antisemitism in the Soviet Union|antisemitism]] and [[LGBT rights in Russia|Homophobia]], was on a panel at [[The New School]] on the state of gay rights and acceptability in Eastern Europe.<ref>[http://www.newschool.edu/eventdetail.aspx?id=61424 Coming Out in the Developing World: Exploring Eastern Europe\u2019s Hidden Closets], New School press release, April 19, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Activism===\n\n==== Documentarian ====\n\n2012 marked another turning point in Lucas' career\u2014he released his first documentary film, \"Undressing Israel: Gay Men in the Promise Land.\" The official film synopsis explains Lucas' mission in creating the film: \"When many people think of Israel, it is often in terms of modern war or ancient religion. But there is much more to the Jewish state than missiles and prayers. In his debut as a documentary filmmaker, adult-film entrepreneur and political columnist Michael Lucas examines a side of Israel that is too often overlooked: its thriving gay community. Undressing Israel features interviews with a diverse range of local men, including a gay member of Israel's parliament, a trainer who served openly in the army, a young Arab-Israeli journalist, and a pair of dads raising their kids. Lucas also visits Tel Aviv's vibrant nightlife scene\u2014and even attends a same-sex wedding\u2014in this guided tour of a country that has emerged as a pioneer for gay integration and equality.\"<ref>Undressing Israel (Official Website) http://www.undressingisrael-themovie.com/</ref>\n\n==== PrEP ====\nIn 2013 Lucas wrote an op-ed column at Out.com where he discussed his use of Truvada (which he began using in June of that year), the medication used as a [[pre-exposure prophylaxis]] (PrEP) to prevent contracting the HIV virus. In his column Lucas wrote: \"The more I learn about PrEP, the more shocked I'm becoming that gay men are not shouting from the rooftops about this potential game changer in the fight to prevent new HIV infections, which we're losing badly. I'm ready to shout about it. Here's what helped convince me: Dr. Robert Grant of UCSF, the researcher who led the multinational study on PrEP, was quoted at an AIDS conference as saying that 'No one in iPrEx [the PrEP study] acquired HIV infection with a drug level that would have been expected with daily dosing.' Was this really possible? Whether they used condoms or not, people who took [[Truvada]], as prescribed, were protected from the virus?\"<ref>\"Op-Ed: Why Are We Not Talking About PrEP?\" (Out.com) http://www.out.com/news-opinion/2013/07/24/michael-lucas-comes-out-hiv-negative-sexually-active-man-prep</ref>\n\nLucas continues to advocate the use and understanding of PrEP in an effort to end the AIDS epidemic. In September 2015 he created his first public-service announcement where he explains the importance of PrEP.<ref>\"Michael Lucas Supports the Use of PrEP\" (Youtube.com) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4O08sbPW8v8</ref> In September 2015 he followed up with his original Out.com writing by saying that PrEP works, and the backlash against the medication's use needs to stop. Lucas wrote the following in his column: \"Despite all the attempted distractions, the focus must remain on the simple message in the new study: If you take PrEP, you will not get HIV. Period. It is time to wake up, stop the endless debating, and take action. The war against HIV rages on, and when scientists actually win a battle, we must avail ourselves of the powerful weapon they have developed.\"<ref>Op-Ed: PrEP Works, So Stop The Backlash (Out.com) http://www.out.com/news-opinion/2015/9/12/op-ed-prep-works-so-drop-backlash</ref> On February 24, 2016, PrEP was formally approved in Israel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/israel-approves-prep-prime-minister-addresses-lgbt-rights-at-knesset/02/2016/|title=Israel Approves PrEP, Prime Minister Addresses LGBT Rights At Knesset}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qnews.com.au/israel-approves-prep-to-fight-hiv/|title=ISRAEL APPROVES PREP TO FIGHT HIV - Q News|website=www.qnews.com.au|date=2016-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Israel ====\n{{see also|Men of Israel}}\n[[File:Michael Lucas Men of Israel film shoot.jpg|200px|thumb|Lucas, under the microphone, on the set of the 2009 release ''Men of Israel'', the first adult film to use exclusively Jewish models.<ref name=\"LAB\">[http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2009/07/men-of-israel-the-new-box-office-hottie.html 'Men of Israel': The new box-office stud?], ''Los Angeles Times'' blog, July 27, 2009.</ref>]]\nThe core of Lucas' [[worldview]] is his [[Jewish]] identity, and particularly his deep affinity for the state of Israel.<ref name=\"Kerchik\" /> His time growing up in the [[Soviet Union]], which was notorious for its [[antisemitism]], meant that like many [[Russian Jews]], Lucas had to repress his identity. Lucas has claimed that he was given his mother's maiden name at birth specifically because Treivas sounded less Jewish than his father's surname Bregman.\n\n[[Hezbollah]]'s attacks in the [[2006 Lebanon war]] affected Lucas, who in the midst of the fighting announced his plans to go to Israel to entertain gay soldiers (who are [[LGBT rights in Israel#Military service|allowed to serve openly]] in the military).<ref name=\"something Bunder Entertaining\" /><ref name=\"ynet Bunder Entertaining\">Bunder, Leslie (August 19, 2006), [http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3293013,00.html \"Entertaining gay Israeli troops\"]: \"Talkbacks\", retrieved from www.ynetnews.com on September 5, 2006.</ref> Lucas received a positive response to the trip; however, some religious segments of Israeli society had expressed less enthusiasm for the arrival of a gay porn magnate.  In an article, \"Lucas responds,\" Lucas characterized some of the reaction as [[homophobia|homophobic]] and in an interview said, \"Israel is my country as much as it is yours.  To come to Israel is my [[Law of Return|birthright]].\"<ref name=\"something Bunder Responds\">Bunder, Leslie (August 24, 2006), [http://www.somethingjewish.co.uk/articles/1985_lucas_responds.htm \"Lucas responds\"], retrieved from www.somethingjewish.co.uk on September 3, 2006.</ref><ref>Lucas, Michael (August 23, 2006), {{cite web|url=http://www.lucasblog.com/archives/2006/08/dear_friends_an.html |title=Dear friends and fellow Jews |accessdate=2009-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061107005109/http://www.lucasblog.com/archives/2006/08/dear_friends_an.html |archivedate=November 7, 2006 }}, retrieved from www.lucasblog.com on September 5, 2006</ref> In September 2009, Lucas was granted Israeli citizenship.<ref name=\"haaretz.com\" /> In 2010, he renounced his Russian citizenship.<ref name=\"advocate.com\" />\n\nThe next summer in a ''New York Blade'' column Lucas brought up his disapproval of [[Haredi Judaism]] in Israel once again.  In \"Trouble With Ultra-Orthodox,\" Lucas referred to the Ultra-Orthodox community in [[Jerusalem]] as \"religious goons\" and parasites for his belief that they take advantage of state welfare programs.<ref>{{cite journal| date=June 6, 2007|author=Michael Lucas | title=Trouble With Ultra-Orthodox |journal=[[New York Blade]]|url=http://www.nyblade.com/2007/7-6/viewpoint/opinion/lucas.cfm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020085104/http://www.nyblade.com/2007/7-6/viewpoint/opinion/lucas.cfm|archivedate=October 20, 2007| format= \u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ATrouble+With+Ultra-Orthodox&as_publication=%5B%5BNew+York+Blade%5D%5D&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>}}</ref>\n\n====New York LGBT Community Center====\nIn February 2011, Lucas created a controversy over a pro-Palestinian group that planned to hold a meeting at New York's [[Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual & Transgender Community Center]]. The group, Siegebusters, had planned to hold a fundraising party on March 5 at the center to help fund another vessel to break the [[2007\u2013present blockade of the Gaza Strip|Israeli naval blockade of Gaza]], as well as to train activists.<ref name=\"dailygay\">[http://daily.gay.com/hot_topics/2011/02/michael-lucas-calls-for-boycott-of-lgbt-center.html Michael Lucas Says LGBT Center Pressed Jewish Group to Move Meeting] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727235152/http://daily.gay.com/hot_topics/2011/02/michael-lucas-calls-for-boycott-of-lgbt-center.html |date=July 27, 2011 }}, Duncan Osbourne, Gay.com news, February 2011</ref><ref name=\"advcenter\">[http://www.advocate.com/News/Daily_News/2011/02/22/Michael_Lucas_Boycott_LGBT_Center/ LGBT Center Cancels Israel Apartheid Event], ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', February 22, 2011.</ref><ref name=\"jpostcent\">[http://www.jpost.com/JewishWorld/JewishNews/Article.aspx?id=209714 NY gay center pulls plug on Israel-Apartheid event NY gay center pulls plug on Israel-Apartheid event], Gil Shefler and Benjamine Weinthal, ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', February 24, 2004.</ref> Lucas protested and claimed that [[LGBT rights in Israel|Israel is the only gay-friendly country]] in the [[LGBT rights by country or territory#Western Asia|Middle East]], that the group was [[anti-Semitic]], and that LGBT people in the [[LGBT rights in the Palestinian territories|Palestinian territories]] are tortured and killed. After Lucas's calls for a boycott, the Center backed down and decided that Siegebusters was not an LGBT-related group, and so they should not use their space for the [[Israeli Apartheid Week]] event.<ref name=\"dailygay\" /><ref name=\"advcenter\" /><ref>[http://blogs.forward.com/the-shmooze/135615/ Don\u2019t Mess With Jewish Porn King Michael Lucas], Michael Kaminer, ''[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]'', February 23, 2011.</ref> Siegebusters protested the decision by organizing an [[online petition]]; Lucas told ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' that his success with the event's cancellation was a \"landmark moment\" in his life.<ref name=\"jpostcent\" />\n\nThe controversy arose again in May 2011 after the center agreed to let the group [[Queers Against Israeli Apartheid]] meet in their building, triggering Lucas to again call for a boycott and an end to the Center's funding.<ref name=\"Bee\">[http://www.sacbee.com/2011/05/26/3656760/new-york-lgbt-center-takes-side.html New York LGBT Center Takes Side of Anti-Semites]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Michael Lucas press release, PR Newswire via ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'', March 26, 2011; accessed March 26, 2011</ref><ref name=\"JTGcent\">[http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/05/26/3087900/gay-community-center-criticized-for-renting-space-to-anti-israel-group N.Y. gay center rapped for renting space to anti-Israel group] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529065421/http://www.jta.org/news/article/2011/05/26/3087900/gay-community-center-criticized-for-renting-space-to-anti-israel-group |date=May 29, 2011 }}, ''[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]'', May 26, 2011; accessed May 26, 2011</ref> In a statement defending the move, the center said that it \"provides space for a variety of LGBT voices in our community to engage in conversations on a range of topics.\"<ref name=\"JTGcent\" /> In a press release, Lucas responded that the center had become an accomplice of an \"anti-Semitic hate group whose goal is the destruction of the Jewish state of Israel\".<ref name=\"Bee\" /> In the beginning of June 2011, the center decided to place a \"moratorium\" on renting space to \"groups that organize around the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Weinthal |first=Benjamin |url=http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=223627 |title=New York LGBT center ejects Queers Against Israel Apartheid |publisher=Jpost.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nLucas appeared in [[Timothy Greenfield-Sanders]]' 2004 book ''XXX: 30 Porn Star Photographs''<ref name=\"XXX30\">{{cite book\n| last = Greenfield-Sanders\n| first = Timothy, photographer\n| authorlink = | year = 2005\n| title = XXX 30 Porn-Star Portraits\n| publisher = Bulfinch Press\n| location = New York City\n| isbn = 978-0-8212-7754-6}}</ref>\nand the accompanying [[HBO]] documentary ''[[Thinking XXX]]''.<ref>{{Cite AV media\n| people = Greenfield-Sanders, Timothy, director | title = Thinking XXX | medium = TV Documentary | publisher = HBO | location = |date= 2004 }}</ref>\nGreenfield-Sanders asked Lucas for a list of his 10 favorite films; the 10 films he listed are all films from his own production company.  In May 2007, [[Kensington Books]] published ''Naked: The Life and Times of Michael Lucas'', a biography of Lucas.<ref>{{cite book | title=Naked: The Life and Pornography of Michael Lucas | author=Corey Taylor | year=2007 | publisher=Kensington Books | isbn=978-0-7582-1750-9 | url-access=registration | url=https://archive.org/details/nakedlifepornogr00tayl }}</ref> Lucas asserts the book was published without his involvement or approval.<ref>Lucas, Michael (May 2007), {{cite web|url=http://www.lucasblog.com/archives/2007/05/about_that_book.html |title=About That Book |accessdate=2007-06-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602174304/http://www.lucasblog.com/archives/2007/05/about_that_book.html |archivedate=June 2, 2007 }} retrieved from www.lucasblog.com on May 2007</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2000 [[Adult Erotic Gay Video Awards]] (\"Grabbys\") '''Best Newcomer\u2014Director'''\n* 2001 [[GayVN Awards]] '''Best Solo Performance''', ''Fire Island Cruising''\n* 2007 [[GayVN Awards]] '''Best Actor''', ''Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita''\n* 2007 [[GayVN Awards]] '''Best Threesome''', ''Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita''\n* 2007 [[GayVN Awards]] '''Best Director''', ''Michael Lucas' La Dolce Vita'' (Tony DiMarco, co-director)\n* 2008 [[XBIZ Award]] '''GLBT Director of the Year''' (with Tony DiMarco)<ref name=\"xbizwinners\">[http://www.xbizawards.com/winners.php XBIZ Award Winners], ''[[XBIZ]]'', February 2011</ref>\n* 2008 [[XBIZ Award]] '''Publicity Stunt of the Year''', ''Michael Lucas Found Dead''<ref name=\"xbizwinners\" />\n* 2009 [[GayVN Awards]] '''GayVN Hall of Fame'''\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Adult films ===\nA complete list of film performance and model credits can be found at Lucas Entertainment.com, including those directed, written or produced by Lucas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lucasentertainment.com/ |title=Lucas Entertainment |publisher=Lucas Entertainment |date= |accessdate=2014-03-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Documentaries ===\n* 2012: ''[[Undressing Israel: Gay Men in the Promised Land]]'' <small>(written, produced, directed)</small> \u2013  co-directed by [[Yariv Mozer]]\n* 2014: ''[[Campaign of Hate: Russia and Gay Propaganda]]'' \u2013 co-directed and produced with Scott Stern\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Michael Lucas (director)|Michael Lucas}}\n* [[Adult Erotic Gay Video Awards]]\n* [[GayVN Awards]]\n* [[LGBT culture in New York City]]\n* 